data = [
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>N-acetylcysteine</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This girl has acute hepatic failure. The likely cause is\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/337\">paracetamol overdose</a>, probably staggered and unintentional. In this\nsetting possibly due to the ingestion of paracetamol in tablet form\nand also in cold/flu remedies.</p>\n\n<p>Only ischaemic hepatitis and <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/337\">paracetamol overdose</a> tend to\nproduce transaminase levels that are raised to this degree (250\ntimes the upper limit of normal). There is nothing in the history\nto suggest an insult that would produce an ischaemic hepatitis. The\nparacetamol cannot be used as a guide to treatment as the timing of\nany overdose is unclear and it is invalid where excessive intake is\nstaggered.</p>\n\n<p>Patients who have taken staggered paracetamol overdoses should\nbe started on N-acetylcysteine therapy empirically whilst the\nextent and course of liver damage is evaluated. Remember that the\nlevel to which transaminases are elevated cannot be used to judge\nthe degree of liver damage and impairment of hepatic function.</p>\n\n<p>Doxycycline is an appropriate treatment for <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/913\">leptospirosis</a> which\nmay present as a fulminant disease with both hepatic and renal\nfailure (Weil's disease).</p>\n\n<p>The fulminant form of the disease is also associated with\nhaemolysis (of which there is no evidence in this case) and would\nnot produce such a profound elevation of the transaminases.</p>\n\n<p>Interferon and ribavirin are used in the treatment of hepatitis\nC. It is very rare for <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">hepatitis C</a> to produce <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1010\">acute liver failure</a>\nrather chronic liver failure which may decompensate.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/130\">Autoimmune hepatitis</a> may present as fulminant hepatic failure\nhowever it is rare and usually preceded by a prodromal illness.\nTransaminase levels are usually measured 10-50 times the upper\nlimit of normal. The use of steroids in this setting is sometimes\ndebated.</p>\n\n<p>Wilson's disease may also present as an acute, fulminant\nhepatitis, however the treatment of choice when it presents in such\na way tends to liver transplantation.</p>\n\n<p>Penicillamine takes many months substantially to reduce total\nbody copper and thus improve liver inflammation and\nbiochemistry.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>An 18-year-old girl is brought in by ambulance from the farm\nwhere she lives with her parents. She gives little history but her\nparents say she has been off school unwell for the last few\ndays.</p>\n\n<p>She has no past medical history and takes only the oral\ncontraceptive pill.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she has a temperature of 37.6\u00b0C, pulse is 102 bpm\nand blood pressure is 110/54 mmHg. She is jaundiced with the liver\nedge palpable 2 cm below the costal margin and there is tenderness\nin the right upper quadrant.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood tests show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>112 g/L</td>\n<td>(130 - 180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>214 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150 - 400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>7.4 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4 - 11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Sodium</th>\n<td>135 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137 - 144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Potassium</th>\n<td>5.2 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5 - 4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>11.4mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5 - 7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>156 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60 - 110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>76 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1 - 22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>240 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45 - 105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>10,578 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5 - 35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>11,254 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1 - 31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>38 g/L</td>\n<td>(37 - 49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.5</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>A paracetamol level is taken and is 75 mg/L.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most appropriate treatment?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398306\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199830\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398306\"><span>Doxycycline</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398308\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199830\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398308\"><span>N-acetylcysteine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398307\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199830\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398307\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Interferon and ribavirin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398309\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199830\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398309\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Penicillamine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398310\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199830\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398310\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Steroids</span></div></div>",
        "id": 210
    },
