        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>MRCP</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The likely underlying diagnosis is primary sclerosing\ncholangitis (PSC).</p>\n\n<p>The diagnosis is made based upon a combination of clinical\nfeatures, cholestatic liver biochemistry, and characterisitic\ncholangiographic appearances.</p>\n\n<p>Abdominal USS would be the initial investigation in this case\nand may show evidence of intra- and extrahepatic bile duct\ndilatation. Ultrasound is normal in up to half of patients with\nPSC.</p>\n\n<p>An MRCP would be the initial diagnostic investigation of choice\nparticularly given a lower complication rate and its ability to\nimage ducts proximal to obstructing strictures.</p>\n\n<p>ERCP would be reserved for cases where there is still diagnostic\nuncertainty (it still remains the gold standard for establishing\nthe diagnosis) or a need for therapeutic intervention.</p>\n\n<p>Liver histology can be variable and show a wide range of\nchanges. Some changes (periductal fibrosis with inflammation)\nresemble other conditions such as primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> and\nchronic active hepatitis. Due to this and the patchy nature of the\ndisease histology may not be diagnostic and a purely histological\ndiagnosis may be incorrect.</p>\n\n<p>Antimitchondiral antibodies are associated with primary biliary\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> (PBC) not PSC.</p>\n\n<p>Withdrawal of his medication will be of no benefit as this\npatient has established liver disease due to PSC rather than drug\nrelated cholestasis.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old male with ulcerative colitis of 10 years duration\npresented with feeling unwell. He has complained of right upper\nquadrant pain and has recently noticed that he has started to itch.\nHis stools are pale coloured. He is on sulfasalazine and has had\nonly two previous minor relapses.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he has five spider naevi on the upper trunk. A\nliver edge is palpable 5 cm below the right costal margin. The tip\nof the spleen is also palpable but there are no signs of\nascites.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>110 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Prothrombin time</th>\n<td>20 secs</td>\n<td>(11.5-15.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>55 mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate aminotransferase</th>\n<td>101 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>38 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>482 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis B surface antigen</th>\n<td>Negative</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following investigations is the most appropriate\ninitial test to establish the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118058\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118058\"><span>MRCP</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118060\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118060\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">ERCP</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118061\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118061\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antimitochondrial antibodies</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118062\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118062\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Withdrawal of sulfasalazine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118059\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80758\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118059\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 211
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Entecavir</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>High viral load is associated with poor prognosis in hepatitis B related hepatic decompensation, and entecavir or tenofovir are therefore indicated in the acute treatment. </li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> related decompensated liver\ndisease. High viral load is associated with poorer prognosis for\nthese patients, and therefore prompt treatment with antivirals can\nimprove outlook. Entecavir or tenofovir are the most appropriate\nmedications, and can be used in combination. However, their use in\nthis situation is not risk free and may precipitate a lactic\nacidosis so careful monitoring is required</p>\n\n<p>Interferon use is discouraged for patients with hepatic\ndecompensation associated with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a>, as it has been\nassociated with life-threatening disease flares and infectious\ncomplications.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Lamivudine alone is safe in decompensated HBV infection, however\nit is no longer the drug of choice in this setting as there is\nincreasing concern with regard to lamivudine resistance.\nAdditionally, entecavir and tenofovir give more rapid control of\nHBV DNA levels.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Ribavirin is used for <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">hepatitis C</a> infection. Its combination\nwith interferon confers more success in treating HCV infection.</p>\n\n<p><strong>References &amp; Further Reading:</strong></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.hindawi.com/journals/ijh/2011/918017/\" target=\"_blank\">Treatment of <span class=\"\" data-bpid=\"127\">Hepatitis B</span> in Decompensated Liver\n<span class=\"\" data-bpid=\"278\">Cirrhosis</span></a>\n &nbsp;</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A patient is referred to Hepatology Department for possible\ntreatment of hepatitis B.</p>\n\n<p>He has stigmata of chronic liver disease. There is portal\nhypertension and ascites. His INR is 2.2 (&lt;1.4) and albumin 25\ng/L (37-49). HBsAg and HBeAg positive. Hepatitis C screen is\nnegative.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following will you suggest for treatment?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118135\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118135\"><span>Lamivudine plus interferon</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118137\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118137\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ribavirin plus interferon</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118133\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118133\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Beta interferon</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118136\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118136\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ribavirin alone</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118134\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118134\"><span>Entecavir</span></div></div>",
        "id": 212
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Insulin resistance</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) is associated with insulin resistance, hyperlipidaemia and chronic moderately elevated liver enzymes.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH) is associated with insulin\nresistance, hyperlipidaemia and chronic moderately elevated liver\nenzymes.</p>\n\n<p>The diagnosis is made only by histology of liver biopsy which\nshows lesions suggestive of ethanol intake in a patient known to\nconsume less than 40 g of alcohol per week.</p>\n\n<p>It is not necessarily benign: cryptogenic cirrhosis in patients\nis a substantial number of probable end-stage NASH.</p>\n\n<div>Further Reading</div>\n\n<p>National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney\nDiseases. <a href=\"http://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/health-topics/liver-disease/nonalcoholic-steatohepatitis/Pages/facts.aspx\" target=\"_blank\">Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH).</a></p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>With which of the following is non-alcoholic steatohepatitis\nassociated?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117802\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80706\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117802\"><span>Viral hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117798\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80706\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117798\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">A benign course in all cases</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117800\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80706\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117800\"><span>Insulin resistance</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117801\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80706\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117801\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Normal level of liver enzymes</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117799\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80706\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117799\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcohol abuse</span></div></div>",
        "id": 213
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>pH <7.3</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Guidelines for referral to a liver unit following paracetamol\noverdose include</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>An arterial pH &lt;7.3</li>\n\n<li>INR &gt;3 (or prothrombin time &gt;50 seconds)</li>\n\n<li>Oliguria</li>\n\n<li>Creatinine &gt;200 \u00b5mol/L, or</li>\n\n<li>Hypoglycaemia.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Any degree of encephalopathy 48 hours after ingestion is also an\nindication.</p>\n\n<p>Criteria for liver transplant in fulminant failure in cases of\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/337\">paracetamol overdose</a> include arterial pH lower than 7.3 or all of\nthe following:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Prothrombin time greater than 100 seconds</li>\n\n<li>Creatinine greater than 300 \u00b5mol/L, and</li>\n\n<li>Grade 3-4 encephalopathy.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Criteria for liver transplant in fulminant failure in\nnon-paracetamol cases include INR greater than 6.7 or prothrombin\ntime greater than 100 seconds, or any three of the following:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Aetiology that is not due to <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/126\">hepatitis A</a>, <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> or a drug\nreaction</li>\n\n<li>Age less than 10 years or more than 40 years</li>\n\n<li>Jaundice more than seven days before encephalopathy</li>\n\n<li>INR greater than 4 or prothrombin time greater than 50 seconds,\nand</li>\n\n<li>Bilirubin greater than 300 \u00b5mol/L.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</li>\n\n<li>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>You are on call and the Emergency department refers you an\n18-year-old woman who has taken a paracetamol overdose.</p>\n\n<p>The paracetamol level indicates treatment should be carried out\nand the team in the Emergency department have commenced\nN-acteylcysteine.</p>\n\n<p>On examination the patient is alert and orientated, there is no\nasterixis. She has jaundiced sclerae with mild right upper quadrant\ntenderness.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is an indication for referral to a\nspecialist liver unit?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398054\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199779\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398054\"><span>INR 2.8</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398055\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199779\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398055\"><span>pH &lt;7.3</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398051\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199779\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398051\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">ALT 1200 IU/L</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398052\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199779\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398052\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">AST 1600 IU/L</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398053\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199779\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398053\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Creatinine 190 \u00b5mol/L</span></div></div>",
        "id": 214
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This man has <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> with portal hypertension, cholestasis,\nand liver synthetic failure.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">Primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> (PSC) has a strong association\nwith <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/43\">ulcerative colitis</a> and is the most likely diagnosis.</p>\n\n<p>There is an increased risk of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/721\">cholangiocarcinoma</a> with PSC and it\nis possible that his deterioration may be due to the development of\ncholangiocarcinoma.</p>\n\n<p>Drug cholestasis would not explain the stigmata of chronic liver\ndisease (spiders, splenomegaly); neither would colonic\ncarcinoma.</p>\n\n<p>Primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> is not associated with UC and is\nuncommon in men.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old male with ulcerative colitis (UC) of 10 years\nduration presented feeling unwell. He has complained of right upper\nquadrant pain and has recently noticed he has started to itch. His\nstools are pale coloured. He is on sulfasalazine and has had only\ntwo previous minor relapses.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he has five spider naevi on the upper trunk. On\nhis abdomen he has a 5 cm hepatomegaly and a tipable spleen, but no\nascites.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>110 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Prothrombin time</th>\n<td>20 secs</td>\n<td>(11.5-15.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>55 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate aminotransferase</th>\n<td>101 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>38 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>482 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis B surface antigen</th>\n<td>Negative</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117491\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117491\"><span>Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117492\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117492\"><span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117490\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117490\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Drug cholestasis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117489\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117489\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Colonic carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117488\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80644\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117488\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cholangiocarcinoma</span></div></div>",
        "id": 215
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Tender enlarged liver</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The most common causes of an acute severe liver injury in a\nyoung woman are:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>viruses (including <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/126\">hepatitis A</a> virus [HAV], <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> virus\n[HBV])</li>\n\n<li>drugs (particularly <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/337\">paracetamol overdose</a>)</li>\n\n<li><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/130\">autoimmune hepatitis</a>&nbsp;</li>\n\n<li>hepatic vein thrombosis (often precipitated by pregnancy\nor&nbsp;oral contraceptive pill [OCP] use).&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The presence of liver failure, ankle oedema, and an exudative\nascites do not help differentiate between these aetiologies.</p>\n\n<p>The ALT of 345 is moderately elevated and compatible with BCS.\nWith viral or drug related hepatitis the peak ALT is usually much\nhigher than this; the ALT may already be on the way down if she has\nhad symptoms for a week.</p>\n\n<p>Tender hepatomegaly is one of the hallmarks of BCS.</p>\n\n<p>In acute severe viral, autoimmune or drug/toxin related liver\ndisease the necrotic liver decreases in size.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 28-year-old lady develops abdominal pain, jaundice, and\nascites worsening over a week.</p>\n\n<p>She drinks ten units of alcohol each week and takes the oral\ncontraceptive pill.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following findings would make a diagnosis of\nhepatic vein thrombosis (Budd-Chiari syndrome [BCS]) most\nlikely?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117434\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80633\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117434\"><span>Alanine aminotransferase (ALT) of 345 U/L (5 - 35)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117436\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80633\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117436\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ascites fluid protein of 38 g/L</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117437\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80633\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117437\"><span>Tender enlarged liver</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117435\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80633\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117435\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ankle oedema</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117433\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80633\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117433\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Acute liver failure</span></div></div>",
        "id": 216
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Alcoholic hepatitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Tender hepatosplenomegaly and fever are consistent with a diagnosis of alcoholic hepatitis, which frequently occurs on a background of cirrhosis.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Tender hepatosplenomegaly and fever are consistent with a\ndiagnosis of alcoholic hepatitis, this frequently occurs on a\nbackground of cirrhosis.</p>\n\n<p>Liver function tests typically show an AST elevated greater than\nthe ALT with at least a 2:1 ratio, transaminases are typically only\nslightly elevated; rarely over 300 and virtually never over 500.\nThe alkaline phosphatase may well be significantly elevated giving\nthe liver profile an 'obstructive' appearance.</p>\n\n<p>The serology demonstrates evidence of chronic HBV infection\nhowever an undetectable HBV DNA load indicates that this is\nunlikely to be causing this acute presentation. HDV infection\ncauses accelerated liver damage with lower HBV DNA loads however it\nstill requires active HBV replication. Liver disease secondary to\neither would give rise to a 'hepatitic' rather than\n'obstructive' liver panel. The same is true of autoimmune\nhepatitis.</p>\n\n<p>Whilst carcinoma of the head of the pancreas would cause an\nobstructive jaundice, it would not give rise to clinical features\nof chronic liver disease.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 52 year-old male presents with general deterioration.</p>\n\n<p>He drinks approximately 29 units of alcohol each week and is a\nsmoker of 5 cigarettes daily.</p>\n\n<p>Examination reveals that he is jaundiced, has numerous spider\nnaevi on his chest, and he has a temperature of 37.8\u00b0C. Abdominal\nexamination reveals tender hepatosplenomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>200 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>550 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>258 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>25 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Hepatitis B virus surface antigen positive.</p>\n\n<p>Hepatitis B virus e antigen negative.</p>\n\n<p>Hepatitis B virus DNA undetectable.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely cause for his acute presentation?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117332\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80612\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117332\"><span>Chronic hepatitis D (delta) infection</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117328\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80612\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117328\"><span>Alcoholic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117329\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80612\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117329\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Autoimmune chronic active hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117330\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80612\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117330\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Carcinoma of the pancreas</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117331\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80612\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117331\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Chronic hepatitis B infection</span></div></div>",
        "id": 217
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Start spironalactone</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The initial management would be spironolactone which is usually\nwell tolerated in these patients.</p>\n\n<p>Both ascitic and urine culture would then be appropriate but\ntranscutaneous liver biopsy is contraindicated with ascites (use\ntransjugular biopsy if absolutely necessary).</p>\n\n<p>Several large, randomised, controlled trials have shown that\nrepeated large volume paracentesis (4-6 L) is safer and more\neffective for the treatment of tense ascites compared with larger\nthan usual doses of diuretics.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 53-year-old male presents with general lethargy, weight gain,\nand abdominal swelling. His symptoms have deteriorated over the\nlast three months and he confesses to longstanding heavy alcohol\nconsumption. Currently he is taking no medication and has no past\nhistory of note.</p>\n\n<p>Examination reveals that he is well orientated, is apyrexial and\nhas a blood pressure of 132/88 mmHg. He has numerous spider naevi\npresent on the upper chest and has gynaecomastia. Abdominal\nexamination reveals moderate ascites and he has oedema of the legs\nup to the mid thigh. No organomegaly is noted on abdominal\nexamination.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>140 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>4.4 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>7.8 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum creatinine</th>\n<td>135 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum total bilirubin</th>\n<td>35 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate aminotransferase</th>\n<td>70 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>220 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum albumin</th>\n<td>30 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following measures would be most appropriate in the\ninitial management of this patient?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117470\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80640\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117470\"><span>Peritoneovenous shunt</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117468\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80640\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117468\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Drain 4 L ascitic fluid</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117471\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80640\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117471\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Start ACE-inhibitor</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117469\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80640\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117469\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117472\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80640\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117472\"><span>Start spironalactone</span></div></div>",
        "id": 218
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Intractable ascites</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Intractable ascites is an indication for a transjugular\nintrahepatic portosystemic shunt.</p>\n\n<p>All of the other options are contraindications to shunting.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 60-year-old man has portal hypertension.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is an indication for a transjugular\nintrahepatic portosystemic shunt?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201027\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129818\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201027\"><span>Severe hepatic encephalopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201025\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129818\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201025\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Septicaemia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201023\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129818\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201023\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Decompensated liver failure</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201026\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129818\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201026\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Severe heart failure</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201024\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129818\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201024\"><span>Intractable ascites</span></div></div>",
        "id": 219
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The features of episodic bloody diarrhoea and the clinical\nfindings point to a diagnosis of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/43\">ulcerative colitis</a> (UC).</p>\n\n<p>Alkaline phosphatase and gamma gluteryltransferase can often act\nas non-specific markers of inflammation.</p>\n\n<p>The raised bilirubin points to a more cholestatic process. Drugs\noften cause this but it is not common with loperamide.</p>\n\n<p>The combination of UC and cholestasis really should point to\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> (PSC) the antineutrophil cytoplasmic\nantibody (ANCA) helps a little (this is not a specific marker).</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/873\">Cholelithiasis</a> is a possibility but rare in young men.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 32-year-old gentleman was seen in the outpatient clinic with a\nsix week history of diarrhoea.</p>\n\n<p>He admitted to opening his bowels up to eight times per day and\nat least twice at night. He described the diarrhoea as bloody and\nalso had an ache in the left iliac fossa.</p>\n\n<p>He recalled several similar episodes over the past ten years\nwhich were self limiting but he had never sought medical\nadvice.</p>\n\n<p>His general practitioner had started Loperamide.</p>\n\n<p>On examination, he looked generally well but had yellow sclera\nwith mild tenderness in the left iliac fossa; sigmoidoscopy\nrevealed an inflamed mucosa.</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>102 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cells</th>\n<td>9.0 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>300 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>90 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>35 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>80 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Aspartate transaminase</th>\n<td>50 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>590 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Gamma gluteryltransferase</th>\n<td>800 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>C reactive protein</th>\n<td>35 mg/L</td>\n<td>&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti neutrophil cytoplasmic antibody:</th>\n<td>Detected</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the cause of the liver dysfunction?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118082\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118082\"><span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118078\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118078\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Autoimmune hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118079\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118079\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cholelithiasis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118081\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118081\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Non-specific markers of inflammation</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118080\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118080\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Drug induced cholestasis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 220
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Vitamin B deficiency</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient is manifesting signs of Wernicke's\nencephalopathy with confusion, oculomotor signs, and ataxia\naffecting gait and stance.</p>\n\n<p>Wernicke's encephalopathy is a medical emergency, requiring\nurgent intravenous thiamine.</p>\n\n<p>The episode has been precipitated by intravenous dextrose\nadministration which has exhausted his vitamin B reserves, hence B\nvitamins must be administered to all alcoholic patients requiring\ndextrose.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 55-year-old male is admitted with vomiting. He has a long\nhistory of alcohol abuse, appears slightly jaundiced and is\ndishevelled and unkempt.</p>\n\n<p>He was started on an intravenous glucose infusion and diazepam\nand he symptomatically improved.</p>\n\n<p>One day later he became confused, developed vomiting, diplopia\nand was unable to stand.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117977\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80741\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117977\"><span>Vitamin B deficiency</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117973\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80741\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117973\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Benzodiazepine intoxication</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117976\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80741\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117976\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Subdural haematoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117975\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80741\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117975\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatic encephalopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117974\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80741\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117974\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Delirium tremens</span></div></div>",
        "id": 221
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Dilated cardiomyopathy</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This man has alcoholic liver <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> with ascites.</p>\n\n<p>The cardiomyopathy of alcoholism is a dilated or congestive\nform.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 58-year-old man has had an enlarging abdomen for several\nmonths.</p>\n\n<p>He has experienced no abdominal or chest pain. On physical\nexamination, he has a non-tender abdomen with no masses palpable\nbut there is a fluid thrill.</p>\n\n<p>An abdominal ultrasound scan shows a large abdominal fluid\ncollection with a small cirrhotic liver.</p>\n\n<p>A chest x ray shows a globally enlarged heart.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following conditions is most likely to be\npresent?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117545\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80655\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117545\"><span>Myocardial amyloid deposition</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117543\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80655\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117543\"><span>Dilated cardiomyopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117544\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80655\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117544\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Lymphocytic myocarditis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117546\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80655\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117546\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Nonbacterial thrombotic endocarditis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117547\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80655\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117547\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Severe occlusive coronary atherosclerosis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 222
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>The final common pathway of hepatic fibrosis is mediated by the hepatic stellate cell</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The hepatic stellate cells reside in the space of Disse and are\ncentral to the process of fibrosis within the liver.</p>\n\n<p>Tumour necrosis factor-a is a pro-inflammatory effector in\nfibrotic liver injury, through activation of the stellate cells.\nThese cells then secrete the fibrillar collagen constituting the\ndefining features of hepatic fibrosis.</p>\n\n<p>Interleukin-10 is thought to exert anti-inflammatory effects on\nthe stellate cell.</p>\n\n<p>Endothelin is a vasoconstrictor in the hepatic sinusoids\n(similarly in the endothelium of the systemic circulation) and\nfunctions by causing contraction of the hepatic stellate cells thus\nincreasing intrahepatic sinusoidal resistance and promoting portal\nhypertension.</p>\n\n<p>Nitric oxide antagonises the effects of endothelin in the\nliver.</p>\n\n<p>Five year survival after liver transplantation is now 75%.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Further Reading:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Iredale JP. <a href=\"http://www.bmj.com/content/327/7407/143\" target=\"_blank\">Cirrhosis: new research provides a basis for\nrational and targeted treatments.</a> <cite>BMJ.</cite>\n2003;327:143-7.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>With respect to liver cirrhosis, which of the following\nstatements is correct?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117699\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80686\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117699\"><span>The final common pathway of hepatic fibrosis is mediated by the hepatic \nstellate cell</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117702\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80686\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117702\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Endothelin causes dilatation of the sinusoids, thus decreasing portal \nhypertension</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117698\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80686\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117698\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">In end stage cirrhosis, liver transplantation is associated with\n20% five year survival</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117700\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80686\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117700\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Tumour necrosis factor is an anti-inflammatory effector in fibrotic \nliver injury</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117701\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80686\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117701\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Transforming growth factor is a potent promoter of the fibrogenic \nresponse by hepatocytes</span></div></div>",
        "id": 223
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Maternal hepatic blood flow does not increase in pregnancy</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The diagnosis here is intrahepatic cholestasis which presents\nwith markedly elevated serum bile acids (cholylglycine).</p>\n\n<p>It presents in the second or third trimester and usually the\nalkaline phosphatase (ALP) is 7-10 times normal with raised alanine\ntransaminase (ALT), aspartate transaminase (AST), and\nbilirubin.</p>\n\n<p>Cardiac output and blood volume increase in pregnancy but\nhepatic blood flow does not.</p>\n\n<p>Treatment options include ursodeoxychloric acid, cholestyramine,\nphenobarbital, and vitamin K to treat the coagulopathy.</p>\n\n<p>ALP rises in pregnancy but not to this extent. The placenta is\nthe source of the raised ALP.</p>\n\n<p>Viral hepatitis is the commonest cause of jaundice in pregnancy\nbut the elevated bile acids make this unlikely in this case.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 32-year-old female presents with pruritus and jaundice. She is\n30 weeks gestation in her first pregnancy.</p>\n\n<p>Two weeks earlier she had been treated by the ENT surgeons after\npresenting to the Emergency Department with intractable nose\nbleeds.</p>\n\n<p>Liver function tests reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>72 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-40)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>700 U/L</td>\n<td>(30-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>80 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-18)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bile acids</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">100 times normal titre</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following statements is correct concerning this\npatient?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117837\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80713\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117837\"><span>Viral hepatitis is the likely diagnosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117836\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80713\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117836\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Varices are diagnostic of liver disease in pregnancy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117834\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80713\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117834\"><span>Maternal hepatic blood flow does not increase in pregnancy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117833\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80713\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117833\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">ALP does not increase in a normal pregnancy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117835\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80713\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117835\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Treatment options include IV N-acetyl cysteine</span></div></div>",
        "id": 224
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Budd-Chiari syndrome</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>In <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/874\">Budd-Chiari syndrome</a> there is obstruction of the main hepatic\nveins by thrombus. Patients usually present with abdominal pain,\nascites and hepatomegaly which develop over several months. In rare\ncases patients may have acute liver failure. Signs of portal\nhypertension are present and patients may develop acute variceal\nhaemorrhage as a complication. Jaundice is variable. Ultrasound\nDoppler or contrast CT scan is often used to make the diagnosis.\nHypertrophy of the caudate lobe on imaging is a characteristic sign\nbut is seen in only 50% of cases. Ascitic tap usually demonstrates\na high SAAG (&gt;11 g/L).</p>\n\n<p>There is considerable variation in the clinical course of the\ndisease. Thrombolysis and subsequent anticoagulation has been used\nin the management.</p>\n\n<p>In the rare cases of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1010\">acute liver failure</a> liver transplantation\nmay be a requirement. Management also includes that of ascites and\nportal hypertension.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/369\">Hepatocellular carcinoma</a> (HCC) is the sixth commonest malignancy\nworldwide. Seventy-five per cent to 90% of patients with HCC have\ncirrhosis. HCC develops in 4% of cirrhotics per year. Patients with\nchronic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> have 100-fold higher risk of developing HCC.\nPatients present with pain, anorexia and weight loss. Clinical\nsigns include hepatomegaly and occasionally a hepatic bruit. HCC\nmay precipitate hepatic decompensation and encephalopathy.</p>\n\n<p>Patients with acute portal vein thrombosis (presentation within\ntwo months of thrombosis) develop abdominal pain, fever and signs\nof mesenteric infarction. In chronic portal vein thrombosis\npresentation is with complications of portal hypertension, although\nascites is rare. Biliary abnormalities may also be seen but\nobstructive jaundice secondary to biliary stricture is rare.</p>\n\n<p>In primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> pruritus and lethargy are the\nclassic presenting features. Patients may have xanthelasma,\nexcoriations as a result of pruritus together with signs of chronic\nliver disease. <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/85\">Osteoporosis</a> is also common in these patients.</p>\n\n<p>Patients with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> commonly present\nwith fatigue, pruritus, intermittent jaundice and right upper\nquadrant pain. There may be features of cholangitis, that is,\nfever, pain, jaundice but this usually occurs following\ninstrumentation, for example, ERCP rather than de novo. Clinical\nfeatures include signs of chronic liver disease and portal\nhypertension. <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/85\">Osteoporosis</a> and steatorrhoea may also be seen.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>You are on call and have been referred a 40-year-old woman with\nabdominal pain and increasing abdominal girth. Her symptoms have\nbeen progressing over several months. There is no history of\njaundice. She has a past history of pulmonary embolism for which\nshe was treated with warfarin five years ago.</p>\n\n<p>On examination, she has mildly jaundiced sclerae. She is alert\nand orientated, there is no encephalopathy. Abdominal examination\nreveals ascites and hepatosplenomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>You arrange an abdominal ultrasound scan with Dopplers which\ndemonstrates and confirms hepatosplenomegaly and moderate\nascites.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely underlying diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398156\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199800\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398156\"><span>Budd-Chiari syndrome</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398160\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199800\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398160\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398158\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199800\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398158\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Portal vein thrombosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398159\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199800\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398159\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398157\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199800\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398157\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC)</span></div></div>",
        "id": 225
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Varices</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has stigmata of chronic liver disease with signs of\nportal hypertension, and together with frank haematemesis this is\nlikely to be an acute variceal haemorrhage.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 38-year-old man presents with frank haematemesis. He does not\nspeak English therefore you are unable to obtain a history.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is shocked with a heart rate of 110 beats per\nminute and a blood pressure of 95/70 mmHg. There is evidence of\npalmar erythema and spider naevi. Abdominal examination reveals\nascites and splenomegaly with epigastric tenderness.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397975\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397975\"><span>Varices</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397971\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397971\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Angiodysplasia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397972\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397972\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gastritis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397974\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397974\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Peptic ulcer disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397973\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397973\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Mallory-Weiss tear</span></div></div>",
        "id": 226
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Inventing recent events</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Korsakoff's is associated with short term memory loss with\nsubsequent compensatory confabulation by the patient.</p>\n\n<p>Other symptoms may include:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Delirium</li>\n\n<li>Anxiety</li>\n\n<li>Fear</li>\n\n<li>Depression</li>\n\n<li>Confusion</li>\n\n<li>Delusions</li>\n\n<li><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/227\">Insomnia</a></li>\n\n<li>Painful extremities</li>\n\n<li>Sometimes bilateral wrist drop but more frequently bilateral\nfoot drop with pain or pressure over the long nerves.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The treatment is intravenous thiamine and attention to the\nconsequences of alcohol withdrawal.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old male with a history of alcohol excess presents\nwith a two week history of confusion.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following strongly suggests a diagnosis of\nKorsakoff's psychosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117571\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80660\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117571\"><span>Inventing recent events</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117572\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80660\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117572\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Visual hallucinations</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117569\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80660\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117569\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Epileptic seizures</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117568\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80660\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117568\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Delusional jealous beliefs</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117570\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80660\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117570\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Impaired long term memory</span></div></div>",
        "id": 227
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Hydatid disease</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The differential in this question is really between hydatid\ndisease and polycystic liver disease.</p>\n\n<p>Hyatid cysts and polycystic liver disease may both present with\nsymptoms as a result of increasing cyst size. However jaundice is\nnot usually seen in polycystic liver disease (presentation tends to\nbe with abdominal discomfort or hepatic fibrosis in advanced\ndisease, complications such as rupture, haemorrhage or infection\nare rare). It is seen in hydatid disease where cyst expansion may\ncause bile duct compression or rupture into the biliary tree may\ncause cholangitis. Cysts in polycystic liver disease will appear\nsimple, loculations or septations should lead to consideration of\nalternative pathologies.</p>\n\n<p>Hydatid disease is most commonly seen in farming and rural\ncommunities. The majority of cysts are asymptomatic but may cause\nsymptoms secondary to mass effect or cyst complications. CT scan\nshows characteristic daughter cysts. Treatment with benzimidazoles\nand surgery is required.</p>\n\n<p><em>Amoeba</em> is rare in those individuals living in Europe\nand it is commonly painful.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/369\">Hepatocellular carcinoma</a> may be painful (although this is not\nalways the case) and patients often have weight loss. Alpha\nfetoprotein is raised in 70% of cases.</p>\n\n<p>Multiple liver cysts may indicate underlying polycystic liver\ndisease which is an autosomal dominant disorder (liver cysts are\nalso frequently present as part of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/481\">polycystic kidney disease</a>).\nCysts can be larger than 15 cm in diameter and cause abdominal pain\nwith gross hepatomegaly.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</li>\n\n<li>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 48-year-old male presents with a six week history of abdominal\npain with associated dark urine and pale-coloured stool. He is\noriginally from Wales. There is no history of alcohol abuse.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he has a hepatomegaly measuring 4 cm. His liver\nfunction tests demonstrate a mild obstructive jaundice and\nabdominal ultrasound scan demonstrates three cysts in the liver,\none is multi-loculated.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely diagnosis in this case?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398142\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199797\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398142\"><span>Hepatocellular carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398145\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199797\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398145\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Polycystic liver disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398143\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199797\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398143\"><span>Hydatid disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398144\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199797\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398144\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver metastases</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398141\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199797\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398141\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\"><em>Amoeba</em></span></div></div>",
        "id": 228
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Psychological factors that may impair compliance with immunosuppression</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Psychological factors that may impair ability to comply with\nimmunosuppressive treatment are a contraindication to liver\ntransplantation.</p>\n\n<p>Ascites refractory to treatment is an indication not a\ncontraindication to liver transplantation.</p>\n\n<p>The remaining options are all diseases which are potentially\ncurable by transplantation in adults.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</li>\n\n<li>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old woman with primary biliary cirrhosis and\nprogressive liver failure is awaiting a liver transplant.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is a contraindication to liver\ntransplantation?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398123\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398123\"><span>Postviral cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398121\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398121\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Autoimmune chronic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398122\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398122\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cryptogenic cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398124\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398124\"><span>Psychological factors that may impair compliance with\nimmunosuppression</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398125\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199793\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398125\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Refractory ascites</span></div></div>",
        "id": 229
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Hepatitis B virus</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>There is a higher prevalence of HBV in the Far East which can lead to hepatoma development if left untreated.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The patient has chronic viral hepatitis and presents with an AFP\nelevated to such a degree that it is essentially diagnostic for\nhepatoma. The underlying cause is either HBV or HCV.</p>\n\n<p>Since his country of origin is the only other detail given here\nthis gives a clue to the cause of his hepatitis. There is a higher\nprevalence of HBV in the Far East, consequently, the most likely\nviral agent is HBV.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 56-year-old man from Thailand presented with abdominal pain\nand a mass in the right upper quadrant. He reported that he had\nbeen diagnosed with viral hepatitis several years previously and\nhad several treatment which he states reduced his disease burden\nsignificantly but he is still a chronic carrier. He reports no high\nrisk sexual behaviour or Intravenous drug use.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Investigations showed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alpha-fetoprotein</th>\n<td>13,500 IU/L</td>\n<td>(&lt; 10)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most likely underlying viral\ninfection?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118040\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80754\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118040\"><span>Hepatitis C virus</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118041\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80754\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118041\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis D virus</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118042\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80754\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118042\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis E virus</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118038\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80754\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118038\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis A virus</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118039\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80754\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118039\"><span>Hepatitis B virus</span></div></div>",
        "id": 230
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Wernicke's encephalopathy (WE)</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This lady presents with the classic triad of WE:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Encephalopathy</li>\n\n<li>Gait ataxia, and</li>\n\n<li>Oculomotor dysfunction.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Lower limb neuropathy is also a feature of WE.</p>\n\n<p>Her occupation, poor nutrition, social situation, and blood\nresults all suggest underlying alcoholism.</p>\n\n<p>The <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1214\">hyponatraemia</a> is mild and unlikely to cause symptoms and CPM\n(related to the rapid correction of Na+) is unlikely.</p>\n\n<p>A brainstem cerebrovascular accident is unlikely due to the\ngradual onset over two weeks.</p>\n\n<p>Liver function appears well preserved (normal prothrombin time\nand reasonable albumin).</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old widow presents with a one week history of\nprogressive confusion and unsteady gait. She works as a barmaid and\nlives in poor social circumstances.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is malnourished and disorientated. She has\nnystagmus and is unable to abduct either eye. The pupils are\nsluggish and unequal. Ankle jerks are absent but upper limb\nreflexes are present.</p>\n\n<p>Shortly after her admission you are called to the ward as she\nhas become very drowsy and has collapsed on the floor.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations on admission were as follows:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>114 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>99 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White blood count</th>\n<td>5.6 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>230 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>129 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>3.2 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>27 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum gamma GT</th>\n<td>440 U/L</td>\n<td>(4-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>180 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum AST</th>\n<td>90 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum ALT</th>\n<td>45 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum albumin</th>\n<td>33 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Prothrombin time</th>\n<td>12 secs</td>\n<td>(11.5-15.5)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>What was is the most likely cause of her presentation and\ndrowsiness?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117754\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80697\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117754\"><span>Central pontine myelinolysis (CPM)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117756\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80697\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117756\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver failure</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117753\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80697\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117753\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Brain stem CVA</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117757\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80697\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117757\"><span>Wernicke's encephalopathy (WE)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117755\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80697\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117755\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hyponatraemia</span></div></div>",
        "id": 231
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>High dose vitamin B replacement (Pabrinex)</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Wernicke's encephalopathy is a result of thiamine\ndeficiency. Most cases occur in those with a history of chronic\nalcohol ingestion however malnutrition of any cause is a risk\nfactor. The classic triad of features is</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Encephalopathy</li>\n\n<li>Ataxia and</li>\n\n<li>Oculomotor dysfunction (usually nystagmus but also potentially\nlateral rectus palsies or conjugate gaze palsies).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The neurological changes are reversible if there is prompt\nadministration of thiamine. Failure to do this results in permanent\nneurological disability (Korsakoff's syndrome).</p>\n\n<p>Antibiotics would be an appropriate treatment if sepsis were\nconsidered to be the underlying problem, however there is little to\nsuggest acute infection in this case.</p>\n\n<p>Benzodiazepines are an appropriate treatment for alcohol\nwithdrawal however there are no features such as agitation,\nsweating, tremulousness or tachycardia to suggest this.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/154\">Constipation</a> may precipitate <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/294\">hepatic encephalopathy</a>; whilst this\nis a diagnostic possibility the presence of oculomotor dysfunction\nis not consistent with hepatic encephalopathy.</p>\n\n<p>The patient's blood sugar is a little on the low side and\nwill need to be corrected. With the BM at this level it should be\npossible to do this with food or drink especially as administration\nof intravenous glucose prior to giving thiamine can significantly\nworsen Wernicke's encephalopathy.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 49-year-old man is admitted to hospital with hypothermia\nhaving been found on the street.</p>\n\n<p>A blood ethanol level on admission was 2.4 g/l. Despite\ncorrection of his body temperature he remains intermittently\nconfused, indifferent and inattentive 24 hours later.</p>\n\n<p>He has no previous medical history of note. His pulse is 72\nbeats per minute, blood pressure 105/60 mmHg, temperature 37.2\u00baC\nand a random blood sugar is 3.9 mmol/l.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is unkempt. Multiple spider naevi, ascites and\na mild liver flap are present. His eye movements are abnormal with\nhorizontal nystagmus on lateral gaze in both directions and he has\na slow, wide-based gait. He has been incontinent of urine on\nseveral occasions during the admission but has not opened his\nbowels for two days.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most appropriate treatment?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398393\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199847\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398393\"><span>High dose vitamin B replacement (Pabrinex)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398391\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199847\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398391\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antibiotics</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398394\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199847\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398394\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Intravenous glucose</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398392\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199847\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398392\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Benzodiazepines</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398395\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199847\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398395\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Laxatives</span></div></div>",
        "id": 232
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Supportive therapy</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>A combination of jaundice, alcoholic hepatitis, hyperlipidaemia,\nand haemolysis is known as Zieve's syndrome.</p>\n\n<p>There is no specific treatment for Zieve's syndrome but\nsupportive therapy is indicated which includes:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>correction of clotting abnormalities</li>\n\n<li>treatment of haemolysis</li>\n\n<li>treating <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/549\">alcohol withdrawal</a></li>\n\n<li>preventing further alcohol intake, and</li>\n\n<li>adequate nutrition.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The spherocytosis is the result of the haemolysis.</p>\n\n<p>Pancreatitis is a possible differential diagnosis here but in\nthe first instance one would request an amylase rather than an MRI\nof the pancreas.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old male who is well known to the Emergency Department\nattends inebriated.</p>\n\n<p>He has an alcoholic encephalopathy with a Glasgow coma scale of\n13. He is jaundiced, describes no symptoms, but is mildly short of\nbreath.</p>\n\n<p>You are presented with his blood results:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>74 g/L</td>\n<td>(120-160)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>10.1 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>137 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(140-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Sodium</th>\n<td>133 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(133-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Potassium</th>\n<td>3.7 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>12 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>113 \u03bcmol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>124 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline Phosphatase</th>\n<td>224 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Total Protein</th>\n<td>54 g/L</td>\n<td>(60-80)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>63 \u03bcmol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Cholesterol</th>\n<td>15.3 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;5.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Triglycerides</th>\n<td>7.2 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;2.2)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Blood film</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Profound spherocytosis</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most appropriate initial\nmanagement for this patient?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118044\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80755\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118044\"><span>Oesophagogastroduodenoscopy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118043\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80755\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118043\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">IV steroids</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118045\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80755\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118045\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">MRI pancreas</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118047\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80755\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118047\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Urgent laporotomy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118046\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80755\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118046\"><span>Supportive therapy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 233
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Echinococcus granulosus</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Hydatid disease is caused by tapeworm <em>Echinococcus</em>. It\ncauses asymptomatic hepatomegaly and is sometimes seen in Welsh\nfarmers.</p>\n\n<p><em>Clostridium</em> and <em>Escherichia coli</em> cause biliary\ninfection.</p>\n\n<p><em>Entamoeba histolytica</em> causes amoebic cysts.</p>\n\n<p><em>Streptococcus milleri</em> causes hepatic abscess.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Atkinson RJ, et al. <cite>Medical Masterclass: Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. London: Royal College of Physicians;\n2008</li>\n\n<li>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</li>\n\n<li>Tofield C, et al. <a href=\"http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/9780470750742.fmatter/pdf\" target=\"_blank\"><cite>Hands-on guide to clinical\npharmacology.</cite></a> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</li>\n\n<li>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 48-year-old male presents with a six week history of abdominal\npain with associated dark urine and pale-coloured stool. He is\noriginally from Wales. There is no history of alcohol abuse.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he has hepatomegaly measuring 4 cm. His liver\nfunction tests are all normal but abdominal ultrasound scan\ndemonstrates multiple cysts in the liver.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely causative organism?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398149\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199798\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398149\"><span><em>Escherichia coli</em></span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398146\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199798\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398146\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\"><em>Clostridium</em></span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398150\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199798\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398150\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\"><em>Streptococcus milleri</em></span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398147\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199798\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398147\"><span><em>Echinococcus granulosus</em></span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398148\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199798\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398148\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\"><em>Entamoeba histolytica</em></span></div></div>",
        "id": 234
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Cerebral abscess</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>A cerebral abscess can present with focal neurological deficits, fevers, and reduced consciousness. </li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The combination of fever and focal neurological signs makes a\ncerebral abscess the most likely diagnosis here. The history of\nalcohol abuse is a risk factor.</p>\n\n<p>Onset may be sudden or subacute over several weeks. Presenting\nsymptoms include fever, headache, drowsiness, confusion, nausea,\nvomiting, focal neurological deficits, and seizures. Rupture can\nresult in a sudden headache with meningism.</p>\n\n<p>Whilst a <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/416\">subdural haematoma</a> would be a possibility, it would not\nreally explain the fevers or tachycardia. A CVA would also not\nexplain the fever.</p>\n\n<p>Whilst the patient is at risk of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/294\">hepatic encephalopathy</a> and\nWernicke's, these would not explain the left hemiparesis.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 45-year-old male with a long history of alcohol abuse presents\nwith a two day history of deteriorating confusion.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is drowsy, has a temperature of 39\u00b0C, a pulse\nof 110 beats per minute, a small amount of ascites, and has\nfeatures of a left side hemiparesis.</p>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117855\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80717\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117855\"><span>Hepatic encephalopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117853\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80717\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117853\"><span>Cerebral abscess</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117857\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80717\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117857\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Subdural haematoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117854\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80717\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117854\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cerebro-vascular accident</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117856\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80717\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117856\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Wernicke's encephalopathy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 235
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Hepatitis E</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Hepatitis E infection does not result in a carrier state.</p>\n\n<p>All the other viral infections can result in a carrier\nstate.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>Which of the following viral diseases does NOT result in a\ncarrier state?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201053\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201053\"><span>Hepatitis B</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201054\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201054\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis C</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201056\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201056\"><span>Hepatitis E</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201055\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201055\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis D</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201057\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129824\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201057\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">HIV</span></div></div>",
        "id": 236
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Delirium tremens</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Delirium tremens is the most severe form of alcohol\nwithdrawal.</p>\n\n<p>Onset is typically three to seven days after cessation of\nchronic alcohol ingestion. It is characterised by visual\nhallucinations, autonomic instability (tachycardia, hypertension,\nand pyrexia), obtundation and confusion. Sweating, tremors and\nagitation are also features.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/294\">Hepatic encephalopathy</a> tends to be characterised more by\ndrowsiness and obtundation. Significant <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/294\">hepatic encephalopathy</a> is\nunlikely to be present if a liver flap (asterixis) cannot be\ndetected.</p>\n\n<p>Opiate withdrawal is characterised by diaphoresis, shaking,\ncramping, agitation and diarrhoea. Autonomic instability and\nhallucinations are not features of opiate withdrawal.</p>\n\n<p>Sepsis would need to be excluded in a case such as this however\nthe patient is hypertensive rather than hypotensive and neither the\nhistory nor examination reveals evidence of a particular source of\ninfection.</p>\n\n<p>Korsakoff's psychosis is a chronic condition resulting from\nuntreated thiamine deficiency and is characterised by both\nanterograde and retrograde amnesia with confabulation.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 57-year-old man becomes unwell on the ward with visual\nhallucinations, profuse sweating and tremors. He was admitted three\ndays ago with diarrhoea, which has now resolved.</p>\n\n<p>He has a previous history of alcohol and intravenous drug abuse.\nHis pulse is 120 beats per minute, blood pressure 190/90 mmHg and\ntemperature 37.8\u00baC.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is agitated, sweaty and inattentive with\nmultiple spider naevi on his trunk and jaundiced sclerae. He has\nmild ascites and a non-tender abdomen and the chest is clear on\nauscultation. A liver flap cannot be elicited.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398376\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199844\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398376\"><span>Delirium tremens</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398380\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199844\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398380\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Sepsis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398377\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199844\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398377\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatic encephalopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398378\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199844\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398378\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Korsakoff's psychosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398379\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199844\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398379\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Opiate withdrawal</span></div></div>",
        "id": 237
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>50%</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has Budd-Chiari syndrome. There is considerable\nvariation in the clinical course of the disease. Three year\nsurvival in patients with chronic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/874\">Budd-Chiari syndrome</a> has been\nreported as 50%.</p>\n\n<p>In acute <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/874\">Budd-Chiari syndrome</a> thrombolysis and subsequent\nanticoagulation is used. Liver transplantation may be required in\nthe rare cases of acute liver failure.</p>\n\n<p>In chronic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/874\">Budd-Chiari syndrome</a> anticoagulation can also be\nconsidered but management of complications such as ascites and\nportal hypertension is key.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>You are on call and have been referred a 40-year-old woman with\nabdominal pain and increasing abdominal girth. Her symptoms have\nbeen progressing over several months.</p>\n\n<p>There is no history of jaundice. She has a past history of\npulmonary embolism for which she was treated with warfarin five\nyears ago.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she has mildly jaundiced sclerae. She is alert\nand orientated, there is no encephalopathy. Abdominal examination\nreveals ascites and hepatosplenomegaly. You arrange an abdominal\nultrasound scan with Dopplers which demonstrates and confirms\nhepatosplenomegaly and moderate ascites.</p>\n\n<p>What is the three year survival in a patient who has this\nchronic condition?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398163\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199801\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398163\"><span>30%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398164\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199801\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398164\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">40%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398161\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199801\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398161\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">10%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398165\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199801\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398165\"><span>50%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398162\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199801\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398162\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">20%</span></div></div>",
        "id": 238
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Female gender</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>HCV genotype is one of the important baseline predictor for response to antiviral combination therapy</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The most important predictor of response to interferon therapy\nis the genotype of the <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">hepatitis C</a> virus being treated. Genotypes 2\nand 3 have a far better response to treatment than genotype 1.</p>\n\n<p>Beyond this female patients are more likely to show a long term\nresponse to interferon treatment. However, some large prospective\nstudies have failed demonstrate this trend.</p>\n\n<p>The following also predict a good long term response to\ninterferon:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Non-black racial origin</li>\n\n<li>Low hepatic iron</li>\n\n<li>Absence of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> on biopsy, and</li>\n\n<li>Younger age.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p>\n\n<p>Peginterferon alfa-2a plus ribavirin for chronic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">hepatitis C</a>\nvirus infection.&nbsp;Fried MW, Shiffman ML, Reddy KR, Smith C, Marinos\nG, Gon\u00e7ales FL Jr, H\u00e4ussinger D, Diago M, Carosi G, Dhumeaux D,\nCraxi A, Lin A, Hoffman J, Yu J.&nbsp;N Engl J Med. 2002 Sep 26;\n347(13):975-82.</p>\n\n<p>Peginterferon alfa-2b plus ribavirin compared with interferon\nalfa-2b plus ribavirin for initial treatment of chronic hepatitis\nC: a randomised trial.&nbsp;Manns MP, McHutchison JG, Gordon SC, Rustgi\nVK, Shiffman M, Reindollar R, Goodman ZD, Koury K, Ling M, Albrecht\nJK&nbsp;Lancet. 2001 Sep 22; 358(9286):958-65.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 35-year-old woman who was diagnosed with hepatitis C six\nmonths ago has attended follow up in the gastroenterology\nclinic.</p>\n\n<p>She wants to discuss interferon and ribavirin therapy and\nwhether or not it is likely to be effective.</p>\n\n<p>Which one of the following is a predictor of a favourable long\nterm response to interferon?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398096\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199788\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398096\"><span>Black racial origin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398098\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199788\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398098\"><span>Female gender</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398099\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199788\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398099\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">High hepatic iron stores</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398097\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199788\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398097\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cirrhosis on biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398100\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199788\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398100\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Older age</span></div></div>",
        "id": 239
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Desferrioxamine</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has haemochromatosis. Management includes\nvenesection, aiming for haemoglobin at the lower end of the normal\nrange and ferritin less than 50 \u00b5g/L. Iron chelation with\ndesferrioxamine is sometimes required when venesection is not\ntolerated.</p>\n\n<p>Cholestyramine is used for pruritus in patients with primary\nbiliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> (PBC) and <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">primary sclerosing cholangitis</a>\n(PSC).</p>\n\n<p>Weil's disease (<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/913\">leptospirosis</a>) is caused by\n<em>Leptospira</em>. Patients are infected when there is direct\ncontact with infection in soil, water or urine. Following an\ninitial influenza-like illness patients develop fever, jaundice,\nhepatomegaly and renal failure. Patients may also have meningeal\nirritation, iritis and skin lesions. The mortality rate is 5-10%.\nManagement includes supportive care; doxycycline is very effective\nif given in the early stages.</p>\n\n<p>Penicillamine with pyridoxine causes urinary copper excretion\nand is used in the treatment of Wilson's disease.</p>\n\n<p>Ursodeoxycholic acid is used in the management of PBC and PSC\nand improves liver biochemistry in both conditions. Its effect on\ndisease progression in PBC is debated. It has no effect on symptoms\nin PSC or patient survival at conventional doses, however it may\noffer protection against colonic neoplasia and there may be\nimprovement in liver histology when used at higher doses.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>You review a 45-year-old man in the gastroenterology clinic who\nhas been referred by his GP with abnormal liver function tests. The\nonly past medical history is a recent diagnosis of diabetes\nmellitus.</p>\n\n<p>On direct questioning he denies alcohol intake or intravenous\ndrug use. There is no travel history.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is tanned, there is evidence of clubbing and\nhe has spider naevi over the anterior chest wall. Abdominal\nexamination reveals tender hepatomegaly 4 cm below the costal\nmargin.</p>\n\n<p>The management of this patient's underlying condition may\ninclude which of the following?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397968\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397968\"><span>Doxycycline</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397967\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397967\"><span>Desferrioxamine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397969\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397969\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Penicillamine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397970\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397970\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ursodeoxycholic acid</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397966\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199762\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397966\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cholestyramine</span></div></div>",
        "id": 240
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Ultrasound scan of the abdomen</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The presentation is not consistent with hepatitis E\ninfection.</p>\n\n<p>Typhoid serology is unreliable.</p>\n\n<p>The differential diagnosis is mainly pyogenic or amoebic liver\nabscess.</p>\n\n<p>Pyogenic abscesses present with swinging pyrexia, neutrophilia,\nand high inflammatory markers. Right-sided pleural effusions are\ncommon and blood cultures are often positive.</p>\n\n<p>The presentation of amoebic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/640\">liver abscess</a> (ALA) is very similar.\nMost patients do not have bowel symptoms at any time and amoebic\ncysts are found in stool in less than 50% of proven cases of\nALA.</p>\n\n<p>Serology is the mainstay of diagnosis.</p>\n\n<p>Ultrasound scan would confirm most moderate-sized to large liver\nabscesses and could guide a diagnostic aspiration.</p>\n\n<p>Small lesions are best demonstrated by CT or MRI.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 22-year-old man presented to the Emergency Department one week\nafter returning from a six month visit to Pakistan. He complained\nof fever, rigors and headache.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he was febrile (38\u00b0C) with a blood pressure of\n115/65 mmHg, and a pulse of 100/minute. His abdomen was tender in\nthe right upper quadrant.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations showed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Hb</th>\n<td>110 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>WBC</th>\n<td>15.5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Neutrophils</th>\n<td>13.5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(1.5-7)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>350 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Blood film</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">No malaria parasites seen</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alk Phos</th>\n<td>450 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>50 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>CRP</th>\n<td>88 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Stool culture</th>\n<td>Negative</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Chest x ray</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Small right pleural effusion noted</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following investigations would be of most\ndiagnostic value?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117745\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80695\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117745\"><span>Stool microscopy for ova, cysts and parasites</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117744\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80695\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117744\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Sigmoidoscopy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117743\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80695\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117743\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis E serology</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117747\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80695\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117747\"><span>Ultrasound scan of the abdomen</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117746\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80695\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117746\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Typhoid serology</span></div></div>",
        "id": 241
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Hepatitis A</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Jaundice of Hepatitis A follows resolution of gastrointestinal symptoms.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The story is classic for hepatitis A virus (HAV) with initial\ngastrointestinal symptoms then improved condition followed by\njaundice.</p>\n\n<p>The alanine aminotransferase (ALT) is too high for alcoholic\nhepatitis which in general is around the 200 mark in alcoholic\nhepatitis.</p>\n\n<p>Acute jaundice in hepatitis C virus (HCV) is seen but is rare,\nSri Lanka is also not an area of particular high prevelance.</p>\n\n<p>Diarrhoea is not really a feature of autoimmune hepatitis or\ndrug induced hepatitis but the latter should be considered given\nthe history of antibiotic use.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 20-year-old male student was seen in the Emergency department.\nHe complained of nausea and he had noticed yellow discolouration of\nhis eyes.</p>\n\n<p>He had recently been on an exchange visit to Sri Lanka where he\nhad worked in a hospital. He recalled some traveller's\ndiarrhoea for which he had taken ciprofloxacin that he had taken\nwith him. Since that time he had generally felt unwell but over the\npast few days had started to feel better.</p>\n\n<p>He admitted to consuming more than his average alcohol on his\ntrip, but was reluctant to discuss a sexual history.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he was clearly jaundiced, there were no signs of\nchronic liver disease; he had a mildly tender liver edge but no\nother abnormal organ enlargement.</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>142 g/dL</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cells</th>\n<td>9.0 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>300 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>90 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>40 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>90 \u03bcmol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alanine amino transaminase</th>\n<td>1550 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>140 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Gamma gluteryltransferase</th>\n<td>70 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>C reactive protein</th>\n<td>25 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>What disease process is likely to be causing this picture?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118073\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118073\"><span>Alcoholic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118076\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118076\"><span>Hepatitis A</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118074\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118074\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Autoimmune hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118075\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118075\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Drug induced hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118077\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118077\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis C</span></div></div>",
        "id": 242
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Inhibits proliferation of ammonia-forming organisms in the gut</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Lactulose, an osmotic laxative:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>causes hypomagnesaemia associated with diarrhoea</li>\n\n<li>is not absorbed</li>\n\n<li>does not affect the absorption of spironolactone and</li>\n\n<li>may be used in diabetics.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>It is used in patients with cirrhosis/hepatic encephalopathy to\nlimit the proliferation of ammonia-forming gut organisms and\nincrease the clearance of protein load in the gut.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 47-year-old man presents with confusion and drowsiness.</p>\n\n<p>A diagnosis of hepatic encephalopathy is suspected and treatment\nwith lactulose is begun.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following concerning lactulose is true?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117738\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117738\"><span>Absorbed from the gut</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117739\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117739\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Causes hypermagnesaemia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117741\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117741\"><span>Inhibits proliferation of ammonia-forming organisms in the gut</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117740\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117740\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Contraindicated in diabetes mellitus</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117742\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80694\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117742\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Reduces absorption of spironolactone</span></div></div>",
        "id": 243
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Contrast echocardiography</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has hepatopulmonary syndrome. This is characterised\nby an oxygenation defect induced by pulmonary vascular dilatation\nin patients with liver <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> or portal hypertension.</p>\n\n<p>This oxygenation defect consists of a wide alveolar-arterial\ngradient (&gt;15 mmHg). The vascular dilatation is thought to be\ninduced by increased pulmonary levels of nitric oxide. It is seen\nin 15-30% of patients with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> and is a poor prognostic\nindicator.</p>\n\n<p>Most patients with hepatopulmonary syndrome are asymptomatic or\nhave dyspnoea with an insidious onset. Dyspnoea whilst standing\n(platypnoea) and hypoxaemia exacerbated by being upright\n(orthodeoxia) are characteristic, and are thought to be due to the\npredominance of vascular dilatation in the lung bases. Blood flow\nto these areas is increased in the upright position.</p>\n\n<p>Desaturation during sleep is also often seen as are clubbing and\ncyanosis.</p>\n\n<p>Contrast-enhanced transthoracic echocardiography is the best\ntest to demonstrate intrapulmonary vascular dilatation. It can also\nexclude intracardiac shunting which may result in similar signs and\nsymptoms to hepatopulmonary syndrome. This is performed by\ninjecting agitated saline intravenously during transthoracic\nechocardiography. In a normal subject, microbubbles are visualised\nin the right ventricle within seconds, which are then absorbed in\nthe alveoli. Immediate visualisation in the left ventricle (within\nthree cardiac cycles) indicates intracardiac shunting. Delayed\nvisualisation in the left ventricle (3-6 cardiac cycles) is\ndiagnostic of intrapulmonary shunting.</p>\n\n<p>Radionuclide lung perfusion scanning can also be used. Chest\nradiographs can be normal or show non-specific interstitial\nchanges. ABGs should be taken in the sitting position to grade the\nseverity of the condition based on the degree of hypoxaemia.</p>\n\n<p>Liver transplantation is the only proven beneficial available\ntreatment, with 85% of patients showing resolution or significant\nimprovement in gas exchange postoperatively.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Machicao VI, Fallon MB. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22447256\" target=\"_blank\">Hepatopulmonary syndrome.</a> <cite>Semin Respir\nCrit Care Med.</cite> 2012;33:11-6.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 47-year-old male presents with shortness of breath.</p>\n\n<p>He has cirrhosis secondary to hepatitis C infection.</p>\n\n<p>He gives a chronic history of progressive shortness of breath on\nexertion and now becomes short of breath walking up steps. He gives\na history of being more short of breath whilst sitting up,\npreferring to sleep with no pillows.</p>\n\n<p>The blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, heart rate 85 beats per\nminute, and pulse oximetry, breathing room air, shows saturations\nof 95% lying flat and 87% sitting up.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following tests is the most appropriate to confirm\nthe diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118607\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80957\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118607\"><span>Pulmonary angiography</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118608\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80957\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118608\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">V:Q scan</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118604\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80957\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118604\"><span>Contrast echocardiography</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118606\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80957\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118606\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">MRI chest</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118605\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80957\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118605\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">High resolution CT chest</span></div></div>",
        "id": 244
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Co-amoxiclav</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>All of these drugs can cause hepatotoxicity, but co-amoxiclav is\nthe most likely to cause a cholestatic picture.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old man has abnormal liver enzymes. These show a\ncholestatic picture. You suspect that this is due to a drug that he\nis taking.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most likely culprit?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201043\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129822\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201043\"><span>Allopurinol</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201045\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129822\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201045\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Isoniazid</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201046\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129822\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201046\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Methotrexate</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201047\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129822\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201047\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Nitrofurantoin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201044\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129822\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201044\"><span>Co-amoxiclav</span></div></div>",
        "id": 245
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Drug reaction to nevirapine</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Drug reaction to nevirapine is the most likely cause of side\neffects in this patient.</p>\n\n<p>Rashes are common on starting treatment with nevirapine,\noccurring in ~15% of patients. Acute hepatitis is also common and\nfatal reactions have occurred with this drug. Serious side effects\nare more common in patients with relatively well preserved immune\nfunction. Patients starting on this medicine will normally be\nmonitored closely by their HIV physicians but may present to other\nhealth services. Advice on their management can be sought via local\nHIV teams.</p>\n\n<p>Acute <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> can occur, though not usually associated with\nrash and temporal association with starting new medication makes\nthis unlikely.</p>\n\n<p>HIV seroconversion can present with similar symptoms and\nlaboratory abnormalities. However, this occurs early in HIV\ninfection, usually within two to four weeks but occasionally up to\n90 days after exposure.</p>\n\n<p>IRIS is unlikely to cause widespread rash.</p>\n\n<p>Secondary syphilis could account for widespread rash and\nhepatitis, and could appear as early as this after recent exposure.\nHowever, in context of recently starting ARVs again temporal\nassociation with starting new medication makes this less likely\nthan nevirapine reaction.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 45-year-old gay man presents with generalised macular\nrash.</p>\n\n<p>He was diagnosed with HIV five years ago and started\nantiretroviral (ARV) therapy two weeks ago with tenofovir 245 mg\nod, lamivudine 300 mg od, nevirapine 200 mg. CD4 count at this time\nwas 350.</p>\n\n<p>He discloses unprotected anal sex with a casual male partner six\nweeks ago.</p>\n\n<p>Blood tests reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>159 g/L</td>\n<td>(130 - 180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>6.23 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4.00 - 11.0)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>154 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150 - 400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Sodium</th>\n<td>136 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(135 - 145)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Potassium</th>\n<td>4.5 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5 - 5.0)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Chloride</th>\n<td>103 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(98 - 108)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>7.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5 - 7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>98 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(40 - 130)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>35 g/L</td>\n<td>(32 - 45)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>18 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;20)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alanine transaminase</th>\n<td>153 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Aspartate transaminase</th>\n<td>129 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;40)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>148 U/L</td>\n<td>(40 - 150)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Gamma-GT</th>\n<td>63 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;70)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Liver tests taken four weeks ago were normal.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely cause of his rash and abnormal liver\nresults?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398400\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199848\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398400\"><span>Secondary syphilis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398398\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199848\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398398\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">HIV seroconversion illness</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398399\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199848\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398399\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Immune reactivation inflammatory syndrome (IRIS)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398397\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199848\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398397\"><span>Drug reaction to nevirapine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398396\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199848\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398396\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Acute hepatitis B</span></div></div>",
        "id": 246
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Ischaemic hepatitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Elevation of transaminases to this extent (more than 100 times\nthe upper limit of normal) generally occurs in only two conditions\n- ischaemic hepatitis and paracetamol overdose. There is good\nevidence in the history of both current and previous hypotension\n(particularly in an individual who is normally hypertensive) which\nis the usual precipitant for ischaemic hepatitis. There is no good\nevidence for paracetamol overdose.</p>\n\n<p>Although <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/337\">paracetamol overdose</a> may explain these liver function\ntests (LFTs) it is unlikely to at standard doses (maximum\n4g/24hours). It is worth considering that dosing of paracetamol has\na weight-based component and patients who are significantly\nunderweight will be at risk of paracetamol toxicity at usual doses.\nThe near-normal INR in the presence of significant hepatocellular\ndamage also counts against a diagnosis of paracetamol overdose.</p>\n\n<p>Neither viral nor drug-induced (statin or halothane) hepatitis\nwould produce the degree of transaminitis seen here. Halothane\ninduced hepatitis typically occurs five to seven days after\nexposure and statin-induced hepatitis in unlikely to have developed\nacutely (with normal LFTs on admission).</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 65-year-old man is referred for a medical opinion by the\nsurgical team.</p>\n\n<p>He was admitted for an elective open repair of an abdominal\naortic aneurysm. This was performed two days ago.</p>\n\n<p>His medications include regular paracetamol, atorvastatin,\nmorphine, ramipril and bisoprolol. The last two have recently been\nstopped.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is pale with no peripheral stigmata of chronic\nliver disease; his pulse is 66 beats per minute and blood pressure\n100/40 mmHg.</p>\n\n<p>Yesterday his liver function tests were noted to be\nsignificantly deranged with:</p>\n\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>34 g/l</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>43 mmol/l</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>14,650 IU/l</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>17,812 IU/l</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>3,127 IU/l</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.3</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Prior to admission these were normal.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely cause of his deranged liver function\ntests?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398356\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199840\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398356\"><span>Halothane induced hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398359\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199840\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398359\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Paracetamol overdose</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398358\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199840\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398358\"><span>Ischaemic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398360\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199840\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398360\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Statin induced hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398357\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199840\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398357\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis A infection</span></div></div>",
        "id": 247
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Gastric carcinoma</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders, Stomach &amp; Duodenal disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>The diagnosis is a gastric carcinoma with multiple liver metastases</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The diagnosis is a gastric carcinoma with multiple liver\nmetastases.</p>\n\n<p>There is a large soft tissue mass related to the lesser curve of\nthe stomach. (The stomach normally has a thin wall although it is\nsometimes difficult to assess if the stomach is collapsed).</p>\n\n<p><script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"/Shared/JavaScript/ddpowerzoomer.js\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\">jQuery(document).ready(function($) {$(\"img[id^=5075]\").addpowerzoom( { magnifiersize: [150, 150], largeimage: 'https://media.onexamination.com/MediaBrowser/images/5075.JPG' } );});</script><img id=\"5075\" class=\"ZoomableImage\" src=\"asset/52.png\">&nbsp;</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>This 70-year-old male is investigated for a six-month history of\na 10 kg weight loss and fatigue.</p>\n\n<p>On examination, he appears pale and an abdominal mass is\npalpable. A CT is requested.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"asset/51.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"239\"></p>\n\n<p>What is the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118024\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80751\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118024\"><span>Hepatocellular carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118023\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80751\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118023\"><span>Gastric carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118025\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80751\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118025\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Pancreatic carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118026\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80751\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118026\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Renal carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118027\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80751\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118027\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Renal tumour</span></div></div>",
        "id": 248
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Chondrocalcinosis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Haemachromatosis can cause articular calcinosis.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This man with diabetes has evidence of liver disease with\ngrossly elevated ferritin which suggests a diagnosis of\nhaemochromatosis.</p>\n\n<p>Haemachromatosis is caused by dysregulated iron homeostatis due\nto inappropriate increased iron absorption in the duodenum and\nproximal small intestine. It is an autosomal recessive hereditary\ncondition which is associated with homozygous C282Y mutation of the\nHFE gene in North Europeans.</p>\n\n<p>Increased absorption of iron results in its deposition in the\norgans, notably the liver, pancreas, heart, joints, skin, and\npituitary. This causes <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a>, restrictive cardiomyopathy,\ndiabetes mellitus, arthropathy, skin hyperpigmentation, and gonadal\nfailure.</p>\n\n<p>Males and females are affected equally, but females are often\n'protected' from the clinical features by menstrual blood\nloss.</p>\n\n<p>Arthropathy is relatively common. It is chronic and progressive\nand mildly inflammatory. There is a predilection for the MCP joints\nand it is often accompanied by chondrocalcinosis. Iron load is\nprobably a major determinant but it does not usually respond to\nvenesection.</p>\n\n<p>Early diagnosis and treatment is critical in <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> as\nsurvival and morbidity are improved if phlebotomy is initiated\nprior to the development of cirrhosis.</p>\n\n<p>Transferrin saturation is suggested as the initial screening\ntest: a level of more than 45% warrants further investigation (less\nthan 45% usually excludes the diagnosis). Genetic screening is then\nperformed. If the usual C282Y HFE mutation is found, this makes the\ndiagnosis.</p>\n\n<p>Ferritin is measured to help guide further investigation and\ntreatment: if more than 1000, a liver biopsy should be performed\nand treatment initiated. If the ferritin is within normal range and\nthe liver function tests are normal, patients can be followed\nclosely. If the C282Y HFE mutation is not present other genotypes\nshould be looked for and if present a liver biopsy is\nindicated.</p>\n\n<p>The goal of therapy is to remove excess body iron stores which\nis commonly done via phlebotomy. Initially this is weekly or twice\nweekly (if tolerated) venesections of 500 cm<sup>3</sup> until the\nserum ferritin is less than 50 ng/mL. Transferritin saturation\nshould also be reduced to less than 50% if possible.</p>\n\n<p>After these goals are reached maintenance therapy is typically\nrequired three to four times per year. When iron overload and\nanaemia are present concomitantly, chelation with desferoxamine may\nbe required. Patients should be told to avoid vitamin C\nsupplementation as this can enhance iron toxicity.</p>\n\n<p>End stage liver disease, portal hypertension, and hepatocellular\ncarcinoma (which is increased up to 200-fold) may necessitate liver\ntransplantation. This is associated with poorer outcome compared\nwith other indications because of increased incidence of infection\nand cardiac complications.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">Haemochromatosis</a> is classically associated with a non-migratory,\nrather than migratory, polyarthritis. This particularly affects the\nhands: in over 50% of patients there is involvement of the second\nand third metacarpophalangeal joints, but the proximal\ninterphalangeal joints, knees, feet, wrists, back, and neck are\nalso commonly involved.</p>\n\n<p>Skin pigmentation rather than a rash is more typical.</p>\n\n<p>Myxoedema is not a feature of haemochromatosis.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/869\">Gynaecomastia</a> is a feature of liver disease/cirrhosis per se and\nnot just haemochromatosis.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">Haemochromatosis</a> can cause hypogonadism which can also be\nassociated with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/869\">gynaecomastia</a> but costochondrosis is a more\nreliable sign.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Whittington CA, Kowdley KV. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12452931\" target=\"_blank\">Review article: haemochromatosis.</a> <cite>Aliment\nPharmacol Ther.</cite> 2002;16:1963-75.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 52-year-old man with a history of diabetes mellitus presented\nwith hepatomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations revealed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>30 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Total bilirubin</th>\n<td>22 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>134 U/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>90 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Gamma-glutamyl transferase</th>\n<td>125 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Ferritin</th>\n<td>1450 \u00b5g/L</td>\n<td>(15-300)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following features would be most suggestive of a\ndiagnosis of haemochromatosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117487\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80643\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117487\"><span>Rash</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117484\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80643\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117484\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gynaecomastia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117485\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80643\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117485\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Migratory polyarthritis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117486\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80643\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117486\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Myxoedema</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117483\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80643\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117483\"><span>Chondrocalcinosis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 249
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Chronic hepatitis B infection, chronic hepatitis C infection</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The presence of HBsAg in the serum is indicative of active HBV\ninfection, either acute or chronic.</p>\n\n<p>Antibodies against <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> core antigen (anti-HBc) are only\ndetected in individuals who have been infected with HBV. As with\nother antibodies generated in response to infection IgM is present\nduring the initial immune response, this is replaced over time by\nIgG antibodies.</p>\n\n<p>Anti-HBc IgG is produced from around 14 weeks after exposure, in\nthe absence of anti-HBc IgM it may indicate cleared or chronic HBV\ninfection.</p>\n\n<p>Presence of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">hepatitis C</a> antibodies indicates exposure to the\nvirus, if detected a viral RNA load is required to determine\nwhether there is active infection. Persistence of viral RNA in the\nbloodstream more than six months after exposure (or acute illness\nif symptoms develop) indicates chronic infection.</p>\n\n<p>Antibodies against <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> surface antigen (anti-HBs)\nindicate a vaccinated individual (the vaccine is based upon the\nHBsAg protein) or previous infection with HBV (seroconversion to\nproduce anti-HBs in the setting of HBV infection indicates the\ninfection has been cleared).</p>\n\n<p>Anti-HBc IgM is detectable between six and 32 weeks after\nexposure and indicates acute HBV infection.</p>\n\n<p>Acute <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">hepatitis C</a> infection is asymptomatic in 60-70% of cases,\ninfection is chronic in around 85% of individuals.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 38-year-old man with a history of intravenous drug abuse\npresents with abnormal liver function tests. He denies any\nhigh-risk exposures for over six months.</p>\n\n<p>His viral hepatitis screen reveals the following results:</p>\n\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis B surface antigen (HBsAg)</th>\n<td>positive</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis B surface antibody (anti-HBs)</th>\n<td>negative</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis B anti-core IgM (anti-HBc IgM)</th>\n<td>negative</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis B anti-core (anti-HBc IgG)</th>\n<td>positive</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis C antibody</th>\n<td>positive</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis C RNA</th>\n<td>detected</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>What is the most appropriate interpretation of these serological\nresults?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398477\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199864\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398477\"><span>Chronic hepatitis B infection, acute hepatitis C infection</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398480\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199864\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398480\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Previous hepatitis B vaccination, acute hepatitis C infection</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398476\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199864\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398476\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Acute hepatitis B infection, chronic hepatitis C infection</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398478\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199864\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398478\"><span>Chronic hepatitis B infection, chronic hepatitis C infection</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398479\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199864\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398479\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Previous hepatitis B infection, chronic hepatitis C infection</span></div></div>",
        "id": 250
    },
