        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Budd-Chiari syndrome</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Although the presentation may be less acute, sudden onset of\nascites, right upper quadrant pain and nausea is characteristic of\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/874\">Budd-Chiari syndrome</a> (hepatic vein occlusion). There is often, but\nnot always, a history of venous thrombosis. The ascites is\nassociated with portal hypertension as indicated by a serum-ascites\nalbumin gradient (SAAG) &gt;11 g/L. Hepatomegaly is present due to\nvenous congestion of the liver and the transaminases are usually\nonly mildly deranged.</p>\n\n<p>Peritoneal carcinomatosis would produce ascites associated with\na SAAG &lt;11 g/L (as would nephrotic syndrome and peritoneal TB).\nAdditionally malignant ascites tends to be somewhat more bloody\nthan the 1,231 red cells/mm<sup>3</sup> found in this fluid.</p>\n\n<p>The white cell count is not sufficiently high to make a\ndiagnosis of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/793\">spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</a> and the absence of\nclinical features of chronic liver disease on examination make this\nvery unlikely.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 32-year-old woman attends hospital with rapidly increasing\nabdominal girth, pain and nausea.</p>\n\n<p>She has a past medical history of type 2 diabetes requiring\ninsulin and she also takes the oral contraceptive pill. She drinks\ntwo to three large glasses of wine on most nights of the week. On\nexamination of the abdomen there is ascites and a tender liver felt\n2 cm below the costal margin.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood tests reveal that:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>117 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>12.1 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>513 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>33 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>45 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>76 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>132 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.6</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>An ascitic tap reveals that the fluid albumin is 20 g/L, glucose\n6.7 mmol/L and the red and white counts 1,231/mm<sup>3</sup> and\n175/mm<sup>3</sup> respectively.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely cause of her ascites?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398213\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199811\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398213\"><span>Peritoneal carcinomatosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398212\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199811\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398212\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Nephrotic syndrome</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398214\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199811\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398214\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Peritoneal TB</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398215\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199811\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398215\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398211\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199811\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398211\"><span>Budd-Chiari syndrome</span></div></div>",
        "id": 251
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Porphyria cutanea tarda</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/234\">Porphyria cutanea tarda</a> (PCT) is associated with reduced hepatic\nuroporphyrinogen decarboxylase activity and risk factors such as\nalcohol abuse, medication (for example, oral contraceptives and\ncertain other drugs), and <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">hepatitis C</a> virus (HCV) infection.</p>\n\n<p>When exposed to light, uroporphyrinogen generates free radicals\nthat cause blistering of the skin.</p>\n\n<p>PCT can be treated with phlebotomy to deplete the excess iron\nstores that exacerbate the porphyria.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old man presented to the dermatology outpatient clinic\nwith a pruritic photosensitive skin rash.</p>\n\n<p>His liver function tests were abnormal.</p>\n\n<p>Histology from his liver biopsy is shown.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"asset/53.png\" width=\"401\" height=\"267\"></p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117759\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80698\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117759\"><span>Mastocytosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117762\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80698\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117762\"><span>Porphyria cutanea tarda</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117758\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80698\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117758\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Dermatomyositis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117761\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80698\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117761\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Pemphigus vulgaris</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117760\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80698\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117760\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Molluscum contagiosum</span></div></div>",
        "id": 252
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Dietary protein restriction</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>There is little evidence for the role of protein restriction in\nhepatic encephalopathy. This may exacerbate the condition as these\npatients are often malnourished.</p>\n\n<p>Correction of hypoglycaemia - 10% dextrose can be used but\n20-50% may be required if the hypoglycaemia is severe.</p>\n\n<p>A full septic screen is essential including an ascitic tap if\nappropriate - ideally before starting empirical antibiotic therapy.\nPatients may be critically ill and signs of sepsis may be absent.\nThere is also a potential role for the use of antibiotics in\nreducing the concentration of ammoniagenic bacteria in the gut.\nRifaximin, a non-absorbable form of rifampicin, has been licensed\nfor and is used in the treatment of hepatic encephalopathy.</p>\n\n<p>Ensure adequate plasma expansion. Good hydration is important in\npreventing renal failure.</p>\n\n<p>Bowel cleansing reduces ammonia-producing substrates from the\ngut.</p>\n\n<p>Patients should be commenced on lactulose 30-50 ml qds orally or\nvia nasogastric tube.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</li>\n\n<li>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old man with known alcoholic liver disease is noted by\nthe nursing staff to be confused on the ward.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is tachycardic with a heart rate of 100 beats\nper minute; his blood pressure is stable at 122/85 mmHg. He is\ndrowsy and confused. Abdominal examination reveals ascites with\ngeneralised abdominal tenderness. He has asterixis.</p>\n\n<p>You diagnose hepatic encephalopathy secondary to spontaneous\nbacterial peritonitis.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the least appropriate management step\nin the management of hepatic encephalopathy?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398042\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199777\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398042\"><span>Dietary protein restriction</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398043\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199777\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398043\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Empirical antibiotics</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398045\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199777\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398045\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Lactulose</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398041\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199777\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398041\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Correction of hypoglycaemia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398044\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199777\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398044\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Intravenous fluids</span></div></div>",
        "id": 253
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>ERCP</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> (PSC). Alkaline\nphosphatase (ALP) and gammaglutamyltransferase (GGT) are both\nelevated.</p>\n\n<p>An ultrasound scan will help exclude other causes of\ncholestasis. It is usually normal in primary sclerosing\ncholangitis.</p>\n\n<p>ERCP is diagnostic and demonstrates irregular stricturing and\ndilatation (beading) of the intrahepatic ducts. It is still\nconsidered the gold standard for making a diagnosis of PSC.</p>\n\n<p>Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP) may show\nmultifocal intrahepatic disease with or without extrahepatic\nstricturing and beading.</p>\n\n<p>In practise most patients will undergo non-invasive\ninvestigation by MRCP in the first instance with ERCP reserved for\nthose cases where intervention (that is, biopsy or stenting) is\nrequired or the diagnosis remains uncertain.</p>\n\n<p>Perinuclear anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibody (pANCA) is\nraised in 65-85% of patients.</p>\n\n<p>Liver biopsy is often not diagnostic but may show bile duct\nproliferation and 'onion skin' changes.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</li>\n\n<li>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old man known to have ulcerative colitis is referred\nto the gastroenterology clinic with abnormal liver function tests.\nHe reports intermittent jaundice and pruritus.</p>\n\n<p>On direct questioning he admits to recent right upper quadrant\npain.</p>\n\n<p>Blood results are included in the referral letter:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Hb</th>\n<td>150 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>82 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>350 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>WBC</th>\n<td>5.5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Neut</th>\n<td>3.5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(1.5-7)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ESR</th>\n<td>10 mm/hour</td>\n<td>(0-15)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>CRP</th>\n<td>8 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bil</th>\n<td>20 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>70 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>345 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alb</th>\n<td>36 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>GGT</th>\n<td>200 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>55 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following investigations is considered the gold\nstandard for diagnosing the underlying condition?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398072\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398072\"><span>ERCP</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398074\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398074\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">MRCP</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398075\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398075\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">pANCA</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398073\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398073\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398071\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398071\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Abdominal ultrasound scan</span></div></div>",
        "id": 254
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Vitamin A deficiency</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The most likely diagnosis is primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> as\nevidenced by:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>pruritus</li>\n\n<li><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/170\">hypercholesterolaemia</a></li>\n\n<li>jaundice</li>\n\n<li>raised ALP, and</li>\n\n<li>\u03b3-GT.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Malsbsorption of fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, K) is common.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 49-year-old female presents with a six month history of\npruritus.</p>\n\n<p>Examintation reveals jaundice, xanthelasma, scratch marks,\nvitiligo, and 3 cm hepatomegaly. She was afebrile.</p>\n\n<p>Liver function tests reveal&nbsp;raised bilirubin, alkaline\nphosphatase, gamma glutamyl transferase, and mildly elevated\nalanine&nbsp;transaminase and aspartate transaminase.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following conditions is most likely to be found in\nthis woman?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117789\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80704\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117789\"><span>Haemolysis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117788\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80704\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117788\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Constipation</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117790\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80704\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117790\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Lymphadenopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117792\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80704\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117792\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Vitamin B complex deficiency</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117791\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80704\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117791\"><span>Vitamin A deficiency</span></div></div>",
        "id": 255
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Anti-mitochondrial antibodies</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Anti-mitochondiral antibodies are positive in 95% of cases of primary biliary cirrhosis.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Anti-mitochondiral antibodies are positive in 95% of cases of\nprimary biliary cirrhosis.</p>\n\n<p>Anti-endomysial and anti-tissue transglutaminase antibodies are\nfound in patients with coeliac disease.</p>\n\n<p>Anti-liver kidney microsomal antibodies are found in autoimmune\nchronic hepatitis.</p>\n\n<p>Autoimmune <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/816\">gastritis</a> is associated with anti-gastric parietal\ncell antibodies, with or without pernicious anaemia.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Atkinson RJ, et al. <cite>Medical Masterclass: Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. London: Royal College of Physicians;\n2008.</li>\n\n<li>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</li>\n\n<li>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old woman presents with a three month history of\npruritus and lethargy. She is known to have hypothyroidism. She\ndenies regular alcohol intake.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there is evidence of excoriations and\nxanthelasma.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood results are as follows:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>75 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>84 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>465 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>GGT</th>\n<td>390 IU/L</td>\n<td>(4-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bil</th>\n<td>15 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.2</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound scan is normal with normal liver parenchyma\nand no biliary duct dilatation.</p>\n\n<p>Which autoantibodies are positive in the majority of patients\nwith this disease?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398004\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398004\"><span>Anti-mitochondrial antibodies</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398005\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398005\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Anti-tissue transglutaminase antibodies</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398002\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398002\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Anti-gastric parietal cell antibodies</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398003\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398003\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Anti-liver kidney microsomal antibodies</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398001\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398001\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Anti-endomysial antibodies</span></div></div>",
        "id": 256
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Liver biopsy</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Liver biopsy is diagnostic of haemochromatosis and is the gold standard for diagnosis. In patients homozygous for the HFE gene, a liver biopsy is indicated where there is abnormal liver biochemistry or ferritin &gt; 1000 microg/l. All liver biopsies should be stained for iron (Perls' stain).</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Liver biopsy remains the gold standard for the diagnosis of\nhaemochromotosis as it quantifies iron deposition and also stages\nthe amount of fibrosis.</p>\n\n<p>Ninety per cent of patients with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> have the C282Y\nmutation where there is substitution of tyrosine for cysteine at\nposition 282 of the HFE gene on chromosome 6. However there is low\npenetrance of clinical disease and <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> also occurs in\npatients who are negative for this mutation.</p>\n\n<p>Serum ferritin greater than 1000 \u00b5g/L is strongly suggestive of\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a>, but it is an acute phase protein and will be\nraised in inflammatory conditions as well as those with high\nalcohol intake.</p>\n\n<p>MRI has high specificity but low sensitivity for demonstrating\niron overload in the liver - it has not replaced the need for\nbiopsy in the majority of cases.</p>\n\n<p>Transferrin saturation greater than 45% is suggestive of iron\noverload, however this can be deceptively elevated in patients with\nchronic liver disease as transferrin which is produced by the liver\nis abnormally low.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</li>\n\n<li>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>You review a 45-year-old man in the gastroenterology clinic who\nhas been referred by his GP with abnormal liver function tests. The\nonly past medical history is a recent diagnosis of diabetes\nmellitus.</p>\n\n<p>On direct questioning he denies alcohol intake or intravenous\ndrug use. There is no travel history.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is tanned, there is evidence of clubbing and\nhe has spider naevi over the anterior chest wall. Abdominal\nexamination reveals tender hepatomegaly 4 cm below the costal\nmargin.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following investigations is the gold standard for\ndiagnosing this patient's condition?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397963\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397963\"><span>Liver biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397965\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397965\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Transferrin saturation</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397964\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397964\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">MRI</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397962\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397962\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ferritin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397961\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199761\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397961\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">C282Y gene analysis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 257
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Liver biopsy</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The patient has <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a>, tanned skin, hypogonadism,\ndiabetes, and arthropathy (chondrocalcinosis).</p>\n\n<p>Liver biopsy remains the gold standard diagnostic tool since it\nallows an estimation of the degree of iron loading.</p>\n\n<p>Whilst gonadotrophin levels may demonstrate pituitary\ndysfunction and a glucose tolerance test pancreative dysfunction\n(both secondary to iron deposition) neither help make the diagnosis\nof <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> which relies upon demonstration of excess iron\nand visceral iron deposition.</p>\n\n<p>Arthropathy is due to excess iron deposition in joint tissues,\neffusions may not be present and examination of joint fluid is not\ndiagnostic.</p>\n\n<p>CT of the thorax (with contrast) may demonstrate some\nabnormalities such as pulmonary hypertension and features of\ncongestive cardiac failure/myopathy which may be suggestive of the\ncondition but is again not helpful in the diagnosis of the\ncondition.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 54-year-old man was referred to clinic with a two month\nhistory of pain in both knees. He had no past history of note,\nother than an appendicectomy as a child.</p>\n\n<p>He worked as a property developer, spending six months of the\nyear in the United Kingdom and six months in southern Spain. He\nsmoked 15 cigarettes a day and drank 30 units of alcohol per week.\nHe had three children but had recently separated from his wife\nfollowing two years of marital difficulties brought on by his\nbecoming impotent.</p>\n\n<p><script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"/Shared/JavaScript/ddpowerzoomer.js\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\">jQuery(document).ready(function($) {$(\"img[id^=2796]\").addpowerzoom( { magnifiersize: [150, 150], largeimage: 'https://media.onexamination.com/MediaBrowser/images/2796.jpg' } );});</script><img id=\"2796\" class=\"ZoomableImage\" src=\"asset/54.png\"></p>\n\n<p>On examination he appeared well. Crepitus was noted in both\nknees. He had sparse pubic hair and both testes were small.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations showed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>145 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>7.5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>350 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>139 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>3.7 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>4.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum creatinine</th>\n<td>82 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urine dipstick</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Glucose (+)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which investigation will definitively confirm the underlying\ndiagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118184\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118184\"><span>Glucose tolerance test</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118187\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118187\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Serum gonadotrophin levels</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118183\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118183\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">CT scan of thorax</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118186\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118186\"><span>Liver biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118185\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80783\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118185\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Knee aspiration</span></div></div>",
        "id": 258
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Liver function tests</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The most appropriate investigation for this woman is LFTs to\nbegin with, to assess if there are any features of autoimmune\nhepatitis, such as, raised bilirubin, aspartate aminotransferase\n(AST), alanine aminotransferase (ALT), and alkaline\nphosphatase.</p>\n\n<p>If this is the case then liver biopsy or further diagnostic\nimaging&nbsp;may be required.</p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.niddk.nih.gov/health-information/health-topics/liver-disease/autoimmune-hepatitis/Pages/facts.aspx\" target=\"_blank\"><span class=\"\" data-bpid=\"130\">Autoimmune hepatitis</span></a> is often seen in\nindividuals with other autoimmune disorders such as ulcerative\ncolitis.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old female with ulcerative colitis is found to have\nanti-smooth muscle antibodies.</p>\n\n<p>Which is the most appropriate next test for this patient?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117751\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80696\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117751\"><span>Liver biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117748\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80696\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117748\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Abdominal ultrasound</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117750\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80696\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117750\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Full blood count</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117752\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80696\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117752\"><span>Liver function tests</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117749\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80696\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117749\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Colonoscopy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 259
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Gilbert's syndrome</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The laboratory tests show elevated unconjugated bilirubin with\notherwise normal liver function tests.</p>\n\n<p>The hyperbilirubinaemia has occurred after an illness (likely\nviral) associated with reduced calorie intake.</p>\n\n<p>Plasma levels of unconjugated bilirubin double when calorie\nintake falls. This may increase bilirubin levels above the\nclinically detectable threshold (40 mmol/L) in patients with\nGilbert's syndrome.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 17-year-old male comes to see you with a three day history of\nsore throat and lassitude. During your discussion he says that\npreceding these acute symptoms he has been feeling unwell for a\nweek or so.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he appeared well but anxious. His tonsils were\nmildly inflamed and there were a few palpable cervical lymph nodes.\nAbdominal examination was unremarkable.</p>\n\n<p>You tell him that you think that he has a viral illness but\narrange a number of fasting blood tests mainly for reassurance.</p>\n\n<p>When he returns for review you note from the blood tests that he\nis jaundiced.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>152 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>92 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>7.2 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>310 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Reticulocytes</th>\n<td>1%</td>\n<td>(0.2-2.0)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Plasma bilirubin</th>\n<td>60 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Plasma conjugated bilirubin</th>\n<td>4 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(0-4)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Plasma aspartate transaminase (AST)</th>\n<td>19 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Plasma alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>105 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Plasma albumin</th>\n<td>42 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely explanation for the abnormal liver\nfunction tests?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118192\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80784\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118192\"><span>Primary biliary sclerosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118190\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80784\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118190\"><span>Gilbert's syndrome</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118189\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80784\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118189\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Chronic hepatitis C infection</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118191\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80784\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118191\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Epstein-Barr virus infection</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118188\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80784\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118188\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Acute hepatitis A infection</span></div></div>",
        "id": 260
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Antimitochondrial antibodies</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The presentation with tiredness and itching, in association\nclinical (splenomegaly) and biochemical (pancytopenia) evidence of\nportal hypertension is suggestive of primary biliary cirrhosis.</p>\n\n<p>The findings of a generalised increase in pigmentation and\nobstructive picture on the liver panel (alkaline phosphatase raised\nin excess of transaminases) are also very suggestive.\nAntimitochondrial antibodies are the hallmark of primary biliary\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> and are found in 90-95% of patients with the disease and\nhave a specificity of 98%.</p>\n\n<p>Anticentromere antibodies are associated with scleroderma - more\nfrequently the limited rather than diffuse form of the disease.</p>\n\n<p>Both antiliver kidney microsomal and antismooth muscle\nantibodies are associated with autoimmune hepatitis. Autoimmune\nhepatitis may present as an acute or chronic hepatitis or as\nestablished chronic liver disease - the liver panel will\ndemonstrate a transaminitis rather than an obstructive picture.</p>\n\n<p>Antithyroid peroxidase antibodies are associated with autoimmune\nthyroid disease.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 41-year-old lady presents with tiredness and itching. The\nsymptoms have come on gradually over several months but have become\nalmost unbearable in recent weeks.</p>\n\n<p>She suffers with hypertension and was diagnosed with diabetes at\nthe age of 13. She reports that both her hypertension and diabetes\nhave been well controlled recently. She is currently taking Lantus,\nNovoRapid, lisinopril and simvastatin.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there is evidence of widespread excoriation and\nsome hyperpigmentation. There is no evidence of fluid overload.\nAbdominal examination reveals mild splenomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Blood tests reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>106 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Mean corpuscular volume</th>\n<td>83 fL</td>\n<td>(80 - 96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>3.1 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4 - 11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>35 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150 - 400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Ferritin</th>\n<td>15 \u00b5g/L</td>\n<td>(15 - 300)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>24 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1 - 22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>29 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1 - 31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>43 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5 - 35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>298 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45 - 105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Sodium</th>\n<td>132 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137 - 144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Potassium</th>\n<td>5.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5 - 4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>8.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5 - 7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>87 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60 - 110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Lactate dehydrogenase</th>\n<td>450 IU/L</td>\n<td>(10 - 250)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Thyroid stimulating hormone</th>\n<td>4.8 mU/L</td>\n<td>(0.4 - 5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Thyroxine</th>\n<td>13 pmol/L</td>\n<td>(10 - 22)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which test is most likely to be diagnostic?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398443\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199857\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398443\"><span>Antimitochondrial antibodies</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398442\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199857\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398442\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antiliver kidney microsomal antibody</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398445\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199857\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398445\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antithyroid peroxidase antibodies</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398441\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199857\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398441\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Anticentromere antibody</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398444\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199857\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398444\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antismooth muscle antibody</span></div></div>",
        "id": 261
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Paracetamol</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Although hepatotoxic in high doses even in fairly advanced\nchronic liver disease paracetamol can be used safely as long as\ndoses do not exceed 2-3 g per day. The main exception to this is\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1116\">alcoholic liver disease</a> where the patient continues to drink, in\nthis setting induction of enzymes and depletion of glutathione\nincreases the chances of hepatotoxicity.</p>\n\n<p>Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs are contraindicated in\nchronic liver disease for a variety of reasons - their\ngastrointestinal side effects increase the risk of bleeding,\nparticularly in those with varices.</p>\n\n<p>Additionally due to systemic vasodilatation renal circulation is\nvery dependent upon prostaglandin production to maintain glomerular\nfiltration. Inhibition of this mechanism by non-steroidals, in\naddition to their other nephrotoxic effects, means that their use\nin patients with chronic liver disease, especially where there is\npre-existing renal impairment, can precipitate renal failure.</p>\n\n<p>The sedating and constipating effects of opiate based analgesic\nagents mean that they can both worsen and precipitate\nencephalopathy; they should be used with caution, taking care to\nensure patients do not become constipated or overly sedated.</p>\n\n<p>Fentanyl is a synthetic opiate whose metabolites are\npredominantly hepatically cleared, it is useful in patients with\nrenal failure as there is less accumulation.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 43-year-old man with known chronic liver disease secondary to\nchronic hepatitis B infection is admitted with ascites and\njaundice. He denies current or previous alcohol consumption. He has\nknown oesophageal varices.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is a little drowsy with a grossly distended\nand ascitic abdomen.</p>\n\n<p>His blood tests show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>112 g/L</td>\n<td>(130 - 180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>12.3 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4 - 11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>45 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150 - 40)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Sodium</th>\n<td>131 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137 - 144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Potassium</th>\n<td>4.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5 - 4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>13.4 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5 - 7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>143 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60 - 120)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>47 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(1 - 22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>65 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5 - 35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>85 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45 - 10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>28 g/L</td>\n<td>(37 - 49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.4</td>\n<td>(&lt; 1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>He is complaining of pain in his back.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the safest analgesic agent to\nprescribe for him?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398206\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199810\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398206\"><span>Codeine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398207\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199810\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398207\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Diclofenac</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398210\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199810\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398210\"><span>Paracetamol</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398208\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199810\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398208\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Fentanyl</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398209\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199810\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398209\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Oramorph</span></div></div>",
        "id": 262
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Is characteristically caused by aerobic bacteria</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>SBP is a frequent complication of the ascites of cirrhosis. It\nis diagnosed by ascitic fluid examination which reveals a PMN count\nof &gt;250/ml. SBP has poor prognostic significance with a one year\nsurvival after a diagnosis of between 30-50%. It is, as the name\nsuggests, a spontaneous event that is not a consequence of\nintestinal perforation.</p>\n\n<p>It is speculated that the infective organism may leak into the\nascitic fluid via the blood or from intestinal overgrowth.\nOrganisms should be cultured by directly collecting into blood\nculture bottles. It is typically caused by aerobic gram negative\nbacteria. Hence, antibiotics such as co-amoxiclav, tazoscin, or\nciprofloxacin are typically used as first line treatment.</p>\n\n<p><em>E. coli</em> and <em>Klebsiella</em> should be considered\naerobic organisms. They are more precisely defined as facultative\nanaerobes, that is to say they reproduce best in aerobic conditions\nbut can also reproduce in anaerobic conditions. Obligate anaerobes\n(e.g. Clostridia) are killed by the presence of oxygen as opposed\nto aerotolerant anaerobes (e.g. <em>Lactobacillus</em>), which have\nexclusively fermentative (anaerobic) metabolism but are not\nsensitive to the presence of oxygen.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>Which of the following is true of spontaneous bacterial\nperitonitis (SBP)?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117300\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80606\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117300\"><span>Is characteristically caused by aerobic bacteria</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117302\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80606\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117302\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Is due to intestinal perforation</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117299\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80606\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117299\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gentamicin is the treatment of choice</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117301\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80606\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117301\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Is diagnosed by culture of ascitic fluid</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117298\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80606\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117298\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">A survival rate of over 50% is expected at one year</span></div></div>",
        "id": 263
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Ursodeoxycholic acid</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This presentation is typical of primary biliary cirrhosis:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>pruritus</li>\n\n<li>lethargy</li>\n\n<li>evidence of lipid derangement, and</li>\n\n<li>obstructive pattern of liver function test abnormalities\n(alkaline phosphatase and gamma-GT raised in excess of\ntransaminases).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Ursodeoxycholic acid is used in the management of primary\nbiliary cirrhosis. It is safe and improves liver function tests,\nhowever its effect on disease progression and transplant-free\nsurvival is debated.</p>\n\n<p>Iron chelation with desferrioxamine is sometimes required in\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> when venesection is not tolerated.</p>\n\n<p>Doxycycline is very effective if given in the early stages of\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/913\">leptospirosis</a> (Weil's disease).</p>\n\n<p>Penicillamine with pyridoxine causes urinary copper excretion in\nWilson's disease and zinc may be used for maintenance\ntreatment.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old woman presents with a three month history of\npruritus and lethargy. She is known to have hypothyroidism. She\ndenies regular alcohol intake.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there is evidence of excoriations and\nxanthelasma.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood results are as follows:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>75 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>84 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>465 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>GGT</th>\n<td>390 IU/L</td>\n<td>(4-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bil</th>\n<td>15 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.2</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound scan is normal with normal liver parenchyma\nand no biliary duct dilatation.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is most likely to be indicated in this\nwoman's management?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398006\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199770\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398006\"><span>Desferrioxamine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398009\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199770\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398009\"><span>Ursodeoxycholic acid</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398010\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199770\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398010\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Zinc</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398008\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199770\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398008\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Penicillamine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398007\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199770\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398007\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Doxycycline</span></div></div>",
        "id": 264
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH)</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>NASH gives a hepatitic picture with echobrightness on USS.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The patient has a hepatitic picture in contrast to\ncholestasis.</p>\n\n<p>Ferritin level is not too high to be considered for\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> and is an acute phase reactant being typically\nincreased in any inflammatory process. It is often raised,\nsometimes quite dramatically, in the setting of NASH.</p>\n\n<p>NASH is common and is typically encountered in obese patients\npresenting with a hepatitic picture with or without jaundice. Echo\nbright liver suggests fatty change in the liver seen in NASH.</p>\n\n<p>It was previously termed idiopathic decompensated hepatitis and\nif not treated in terms of lowering BMI and reducing fat intake can\nlead on to irreversible cirrhosis.</p>\n\n<p>Gallstones are a distraction in this history.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 56-year-old female is noted to have hepatomegaly. Six years\nago she was diagnosed with diabetes mellitus and takes metformin\n500 mg tds and gliclazide 80 mg bd. She drinks approximately 15\nunits of alcohol weekly and stopped smoking 10 years ago.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she has a BMI of 36.2 kg/m<sup>2</sup>, no\nstigmata of liver disease are evident but she has 6 cm\nhepatomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Total bilirubin</th>\n<td>11 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>145 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>100 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>150 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>40 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Ferritin</th>\n<td>434 \u00b5g/L</td>\n<td>(15-300)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Ultrasound of the abdomen reveals an echobright appearance of\nthe liver and gallstones in the gallbladder.</p>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely cause of her liver disease?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117365\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80619\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117365\"><span>Gallstone disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117364\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80619\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117364\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Drug induced hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117366\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80619\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117366\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Haemochromatosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117363\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80619\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117363\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcoholic liver disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117367\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80619\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117367\"><span>Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH)</span></div></div>",
        "id": 265
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary biliary cirrhosis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Biliary tree, Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>The two main conditions causing pigmentation and chronic liver disease are primary biliary cirrhosis (PBC) and haemochromatosis.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This woman has clinical evidence of chronic liver disease and\nportal hypertension.</p>\n\n<p>The two main conditions causing pigmentation and chronic liver\ndisease are primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> (PBC) and\nhaemochromatosis.</p>\n\n<p>PBC is a chronic cholestatic inflammatory liver disease, the\naetiology of which is probably autoimmune. It most commonly affects\nmiddle-aged women.</p>\n\n<p>There is jaundice with skin pigmentation, risk of developing\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/815\">oesophageal varices</a> and fat malabsorption, leading to deficiency of\nthe vitamins A, D, E, K (hence <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/517\">osteomalacia</a> and also bruising).</p>\n\n<p>Serum antimitochondrial antibody is positive in 95-99%\ncases.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 48-year-old woman complains of pruritus, steatorrhoea, and\nbruising.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is jaundiced, pigmented with spider naevi and\nhepatosplenomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely underlying diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117294\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117294\"><span>Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117293\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117293\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Autoimmune hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117297\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117297\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Wilson's disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117296\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117296\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117295\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80605\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117295\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcoholic liver disease</span></div></div>",
        "id": 266
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Naloxone</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient with chronic liver disease presents with features\nof decompensation associated with chronic pancreatitis.</p>\n\n<p>Patients with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1116\">alcoholic liver disease</a> are often surprisingly\nsensitive to opiate analgesia, which should only be used with\ncaution.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 44-year-old male with a 4-year history of alcoholic liver\ndisease presents with abdominal pain and confusion.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is mildly confused, but orientated, with a\nGlasgow coma scale of 15. He appears jaundiced, with spider naevi\nand clubbing of the fingers. His temperature is 37\u00b0C, with a blood\npressure of 122/88 mmHg.</p>\n\n<p>Gynaecomastia is noted and abdominal examination reveals a\nmildly distended abdomen with left hypochondrial tenderness. No\norganomegaly is noted.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>149 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>7.2 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>279 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>139 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>3.9 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>6.5 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum creatinine</th>\n<td>95 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Plasma glucose</th>\n<td>5.5 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.0-6.0)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>65 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>150 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>110 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline Phosphatase</th>\n<td>450 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Gamma GT</th>\n<td>500 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Amylase</th>\n<td>700 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;150)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>He was commenced on an intravenous 5% dextrose infusion and was\nprescribed dihydrocodeine regularly for abdominal pain thought to\nbe associated with chronic pancreatitis. However, over the next 24\nhours he became increasingly drowsy associated with a deterioration\nin his Glasgow coma scale to 8.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following agents should be administered\ninitially?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117629\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80672\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117629\"><span>Flumazenil</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117628\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80672\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117628\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cefotaxime</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117632\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80672\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117632\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Vitamin K</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117631\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80672\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117631\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Thiamine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117630\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80672\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117630\"><span>Naloxone</span></div></div>",
        "id": 267
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Patients with non-alcoholic fatty liver disease have raised ALT\nand AST with elevated GGT but normal ALP. ALT is higher than AST.\nFurther testing will typically demonstrate raised fasting\ncholesterol, lipids and/or glucose.</p>\n\n<p>Ultrasound, CT and MRI will all demonstrate a fatty liver.\nDiffuse and heterogeneously increased echogenicity and vascular\nblurring are classical features of steatosis (fatty infiltration)\non ultrasound. In non-alcoholic fatty liver disease histological\nfeatures are similar to those of alcohol-related liver disease but\nin cases where there is no significant alcohol intake.</p>\n\n<p>In alcoholic hepatitis alanine aminotransferase (ALT) and\naspartate aminotransferase (AST) are characteristically less than\nthree times the upper limit of normal with AST higher than the ALT\nin the majority of cases. Patients may also have leucocytosis,\nthrombocytopenia and macrocytosis.</p>\n\n<p>Primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> (PBC) and primary sclerosing\ncholangitis (PSC) are both cholestatic disorders. In PBC alkaline\nphosphatase (ALP) and gammaglutamyltransferase (GGT) are elevated\nwith the transaminases only mildly raised. PSC is similar with AST\nand ALT less than five times the upper limit of normal.</p>\n\n<p>The history is not suggestive of hepatitis secondary to\ndrugs.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old woman is incidentally found to have abnormal liver\nfunction tests. There is no history of high alcohol intake and she\nhas no past medical history. There is no family history of liver\ndisease.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there are no stigmata of chronic liver disease\nbut she has a palpable liver 3 cm below the right costal\nmargin.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood results are as follows:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Hb</th>\n<td>130 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>94 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>WBC</th>\n<td>5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>200 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>CRP</th>\n<td>10 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bil</th>\n<td>15 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>310 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>130 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>260 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>GGT</th>\n<td>100 U/L</td>\n<td>(4-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>37 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound scan is reported as showing an enlarged\nliver with diffusely increased and heterogeneous echogenicity.</p>\n\n<p>What is the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398130\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199794\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398130\"><span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398129\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199794\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398129\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398127\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199794\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398127\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Drug-induced hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398126\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199794\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398126\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcoholic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398128\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199794\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398128\"><span>Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease</span></div></div>",
        "id": 268
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Serum bilirubin levels are decreased by liver enzyme inducers</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Gilbert's syndrome is typically inherited in an autosomal\nrecessive fashion and affects 2-5% of the population.</p>\n\n<p>The mutation in this instance is in the promoter region of the\ngene and leads to lower enzyme levels, penetrance is incomplete\n(not all individuals homozygous for the mutation have\nGilbert's).</p>\n\n<p>A missense mutation in the UDPGT gene can give rise to\nGilbert's. In this case inheritance appears to be autosomal\ndominant. This mutation is substantially less common than that\noccurring in the promoter region and appears to have been described\npredominantly in those of Asian descent.</p>\n\n<p>In both cases UDP glucuronyl transferase levels are reduced\nleading to an unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia.</p>\n\n<p>Whilst serum bilirubin levels are elevated the other LFT's\nare normal. Jaundice deepens after a period of fasting or\nintercurrent illness but bilirubin levels are reduced by enzyme\ninducers such as phenobarbitone.</p>\n\n<p>As unconjugated bilirubin is tightly bound to albumin it cannot\ncross the glomerulus and is therefore not found in the urine. This\ncontrasts with the bilirubin-glucuronide-albumin complex formed in\npatients with cholestatic jaundice (and raised conjugated bilirubin\nlevels) where 1% of the complex is dialysable and although most of\nthe bilirubin is reabsorbed in the proximal tubule some bilirubin\nis detectable in the urine.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Online Mendelian Inheritance in Man. <a href=\"http://omim.org/entry/143500\" target=\"_blank\">Gilbert\nSyndrome.</a></p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>Which of the following is true of Gilbert's syndrome?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118012\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80748\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118012\"><span>There is bilirubinuria</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118011\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80748\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118011\"><span>Serum bilirubin levels are decreased by liver enzyme inducers</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118010\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80748\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118010\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Serum bilirubin levels are decreased by fasting</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118009\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80748\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118009\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Serum conjugated bilirubin levels are elevated</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118008\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80748\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118008\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Inheritance is usually autosomal dominant</span></div></div>",
        "id": 269
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Hepatocellular carcinoma</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) is diagnostic here. At such a level\nin a cirrhotic the most likely diagnosis is hepatocellular\ncarcinoma (HCC). There is little to support hepatitis.</p>\n\n<p>Please take note of the low bilirubin which is usually very\nelevated in alcoholic hepatitis (AH). The large liver and ascites\noccur in Budd-Chiari but the liver is tender especially if acute.\nIf it is more chronic you would expect increased bilirubin and the\nAFP does not fit.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/260\">Ovarian cancer</a> runs in families and increases CA125. Small\nincreases in CA125 can be seen in conditions which cause irritation\nof the peritoneum such as the presence of ascites.</p>\n\n<p>Portal vein thrombosis is more common in <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> and may occur\nin the setting of HCC due to hypercoagulability or portal vein\ninvasion by tumour.</p>\n\n<p>In those with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> there may be worsening of hepatic\nfunction associated with development of portal vein thrombus (PVT)\nincluding the development of ascites. Liver size is not enlarged\ndue to PVT and PVT does not provide an adequate explanation for all\nthe features associated with this case.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 56-year-old lady with proven cirrhosis (which is secondary to\nalcoholic liver disease) and chronic hepatitis C virus infection\nwas reviewed in the clinic.</p>\n\n<p>She had failed previous interferon alpha therapy and continued\nto consume alcohol. She attended every six months for a liver\nultrasound and alpha fetoprotein levels. On questioning she\nreported a decreased appetite and also increasing lethargy.</p>\n\n<p>She had a longstanding history of depression since the death of\nher mother from ovarian cancer fifteen years earlier. At that time\nher alcohol consumption increased and she lost her job as a primary\nschool teacher.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she appeared cachetic and pale but she was not\nclinically jaundiced and there was no liver flap. Her pulse was 90\nbeats per minute and regular with a blood pressure of 110/65 mmHg.\nHeart sounds were normal and the chest was clear on auscultation.\nHer abdomen was soft and non-tender, she had marked hepatomegaly\nwhich had not previously been noted and shifting dullness.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations revealed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>142 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>101 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>110 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>International normalised ratio</th>\n<td>2.0</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum albumin</th>\n<td>29 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum total bilirubin</th>\n<td>20 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate transaminase</th>\n<td>70 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>500 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum gamma-GT</th>\n<td>60 U/L</td>\n<td>(4-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alpha-fetoprotein</th>\n<td>2000 kU/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum CA-125</th>\n<td>400 U/mL</td>\n<td>(&lt;35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum CA19-9</th>\n<td>70 U/mL</td>\n<td>(&lt;33)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118083\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118083\"><span>Alcoholic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118085\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118085\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Carcinoma of the ovary</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118084\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118084\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Budd-Chiari syndrome</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118087\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118087\"><span>Hepatocellular carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118086\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118086\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Portal vein thrombosis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 270
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>No antiviral therapy but monitor serology</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Patients who are positive for HBsAg for more than six months but\nare HBeAg negative, HBV DNA negative and have normal ALT do not\nrequire liver biopsy nor do they require antiviral therapy, but\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> serology and ALT should be monitored annually.</p>\n\n<p>A liver biopsy would be undertaken where the liver function\ntests are persistently abnormal; there are imaging (US or\nfibroscan), clinical or biochemical features to suggest significant\nfibrosis with elevated HBV DNA levels (typically &lt;2000\nIU/ml).</p>\n\n<p>Abnormal LFTs with undetectable or very low HBV DNA levels would\nmerit consideration of biopsy, however one would need to think\nabout alternative reasons for abnormalities in the liver enzymes\nand this may be the main reason for biopsy.</p>\n\n<p>Antiviral would not be indicated unless biopsy suggested\nsignificant disease due to HBV.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006. p 373.</p>\n\n<p>European Association for the Study of the Liver (EASL). <a href=\"http://www.easl.eu/medias/cpg/issue8/English-Report.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Revised Clinical Practice Guidelines on the\nManagement of Chronic <span class=\"\" data-bpid=\"127\">Hepatitis B</span></a>.&nbsp;</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 30-year-old lady is found to be hepatitis B surface antigen\npositive. This positive result has persisted for more than six\nmonths.</p>\n\n<p>Hepatitis B envelope antigen (HBeAg) is negative. HBV DNA is\nnegative. Her liver function tests are all entirely normal.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following options would be the best for further\nmanagement?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398139\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199796\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398139\"><span>No liver biopsy but antiviral therapy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398140\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199796\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398140\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Progress to antiviral therapy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398137\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199796\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398137\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy but no antiviral therapy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398138\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199796\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398138\"><span>No antiviral therapy but monitor serology</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398136\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199796\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398136\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy and antiviral therapy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 271
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Laparoscopic peritoneal biopsy and culture</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has stigmata of chronic liver disease both on\nexamination and on blood tests.</p>\n\n<p>The ascitic fluid has a low (&lt;11 g/L) serum ascites albumin\ngradient (SAAG) making it an exudate. However the fluid has a\nmarkedly elevated white cell count which is predominantly\nlymphocytic. This is very suggestive of tubercular infection of\nascitic fluid.</p>\n\n<p>Her background is one at risk of tuberculosis and the extensive\nlymphadenopathy is also suggestive. The most sensitive test to\nestablish the diagnosis is visually directed (laparoscopic)\nperitoneal biopsy with histology and culture for TB.</p>\n\n<p>An alternative in this setting might be to perform fine needle\naspiration or excision biopsy of one of the palpable lymph\nnodes.</p>\n\n<p>Tubercular peritonitis represents secondary infection of\nperitoneal fluid. Whilst this may be in the context of disseminated\ntubercular infection there is unlikely to be significant disease\nwithin the liver which would be revealed by biopsy.</p>\n\n<p>Liver biopsy would not necessarily be helpful in determining the\nunderlying cause of chronic liver disease as in this woman it is\nprobably viral hepatitis which would be diagnosed using serological\nmarkers. If chronic viral hepatitis is proven, liver biopsy may be\nindicated as part of the management in order to establish the\ndegree of inflammation and fibrosis.</p>\n\n<p>The ascitic fluid findings are not suggestive of underlying\nmalignancy which would more easily be diagnosed on biopsy of a\nlymph node, or of the liver if a suitable focal lesion were\nfound.</p>\n\n<p>Ascitic fluid culture may well yield tuberculosis, however the\nsensitivity of this method is inferior to that of directed\nperitoneal biopsy and culture.</p>\n\n<p>Tuberculin skin testing will only determine whether the patient\nhas been exposed to tuberculosis in the past or vaccinated with BCG\n- it is highly likely to be positive in this patient even in the\nabsence of active TB infection.</p>\n\n<p>Triple phase CT of the liver is an effective way of determining\nthe presence of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/369\">hepatocellular carcinoma</a> and is occasionally used\nas a method of screening in patients at risk (chronic liver\ndisease). It is not a suitable means of diagnosing peritoneal\nTB.</p>\n\n<p>The SAAG has become more favoured in helping to characterize\nascites fluid. The concept surrounds oncotic-hydrostatic\nbalance.</p>\n\n<p>Simple calculation:</p>\n\n<p>SAAG = Serum albumin \u2212 Ascites albumin</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>SAAG &gt; 11 g/L</th>\n<th>SAAG &lt; 11 g/L</th>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">Cirrhosis</a></li>\n\n<li>Alcoholic Hepatitis</li>\n\n<li>Cardiac Ascites</li>\n\n<li>\"Mixed Ascites\"</li>\n\n<li>Massive Liver Metastasis</li>\n\n<li>Fulminant Hepatic Failure</li>\n\n<li><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/874\">Budd-Chiari Syndrome</a></li>\n\n<li>Portal Vein Thrombosis</li>\n\n<li>Veno-Occlusive Disease</li>\n\n<li>Myxedema</li>\n\n<li>Fatty Liver of Pregnancy</li>\n\n<li>Nephrotic syndrome</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n<td>\n<ul>\n<li>Peritoneal Carcinomatosis</li>\n\n<li>Tuberculous Peritonitis</li>\n\n<li>Pancreatic Ascites</li>\n\n<li>Bowel Obstruction</li>\n\n<li>Biliary Ascites</li>\n\n<li>Nephrotic Syndrome</li>\n\n<li>Posteroperative Lymphatic Leak</li>\n\n<li>Serositis in Connective Tissue Disease</li>\n</ul>\n</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>(Table adapted from <a href=\"https://lifeinthefastlane.com/investigations/paracentesis/\" target=\"_blank\">Peritoneal Fluid Analysis.</a>)</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old woman of Bangladeshi origin presents to the\nEmergency department with abdominal pain and distension. She denies\nany alcohol whatsoever.</p>\n\n<p>Her family report that she has become progressively weaker and\nfrail over the last seven months.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is jaundiced with numerous spider naevi and\nhas mild asterixis. Firm, enlarged lymph nodes can be palpated in\nboth cervical chains and the left axilla. Her abdomen is grossly\ndistended and shifting dullness is present, no organomegaly can be\npalpated. There is pitting oedema to the knee.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood tests reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>73 g/L</td>\n<td>(13.0-18.0)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>14.7 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>102 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>156 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>113 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>34 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>20 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>17 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>C reactive protein</th>\n<td>113 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.5</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>An ascitic tap is performed and 50 ml of clear yellow fluid are\neasily aspirated from the abdominal cavity. Analysis of the fluid\ndemonstrates that the fluid white cell count is 1,670\ncells/mm<sup>3</sup> (25% neutrophils), red cell count\n1,684/mm<sup>3</sup> and albumin is 7 g/L, and both the Gram stain\nand Ziehl-Neelsen stain are negative.</p>\n\n<p>Which test is most likely to be diagnostic for the cause of\nascitic fluid findings?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398230\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199814\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398230\"><span>Tuberculin skin testing</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398226\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199814\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398226\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ascitic fluid culture</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398229\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199814\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398229\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Triple phase CT liver</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398227\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199814\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398227\"><span>Laparoscopic peritoneal biopsy and culture</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398228\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199814\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398228\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 272
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Granuloma formation </span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Granuloma formation is not classically seen in liver cirrhosis.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Granuloma formation is not classically seen in <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a>, which\ncan be micro- or macronodular in type.</p>\n\n<p>In the micronodular form, the nodules are less than 3 mm across\nwith uniform liver involvement, as seen in alcohol or biliary\ndisease.</p>\n\n<p>In the macronodular form there are larger nodules, classically\nseen in chronic viral hepatitis.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Further Reading:</strong></p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Loyola University Chicago, Stritch School of Medicine. <a href=\"http://www.meddean.luc.edu/lumen/MedEd/orfpath/cirhosis.htm\" target=\"_blank\">Liver Cirrhosis.</a></li>\n\n<li>University of Connecticut Health Center. <a href=\"http://radiology.uchc.edu/eAtlas/GI/578.htm\" target=\"_blank\"><span class=\"\" data-bpid=\"278\">Cirrhosis</span> of the Liver.</a></li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 65-year-old man is referred with abnormal liver function and\nundergoes a liver biopsy.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following count against hepatic cirrhosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117541\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80654\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117541\"><span>Nodular regeneration</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117540\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80654\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117540\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver cell necrosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117538\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80654\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117538\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Fibrous septa formation\n\n\n</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117539\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80654\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117539\"><span>Granuloma formation\n</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117542\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80654\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117542\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Subendothelial fibrosis\n</span></div></div>",
        "id": 273
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Antimitochondrial</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> (PBC) is a slowly progressive\nautoimmune disease of the liver that primarily affects women in\ntheir fifth decade.</p>\n\n<p>It is characterised by portal inflammation and immune-mediated\ndestruction of the intrahepatic bile ducts which results in reduced\nbile secretion and retention of toxic substances. This leads to\nfurther hepatic damage, fibrosis, and cirrhosis.</p>\n\n<p>Serologically, PBC is characterised by antimitochondrial\nantibodies, which are present in 90-95% of patients (often before\nclinical signs develop) and have a specificity of 98%.</p>\n\n<p>These antibodies are specific for the E2 subunit of the pyruvate\ndehydrogenase complex and it is unclear why they affect only the\nliver when all nucleated cells contain mitochondria. Twin and\nfamily studies suggest there is a significant genetic\npredisposition. Treatment is empirical and patients may go on to\nrequire a liver transplant.</p>\n\n<p>Anticardiolipin antibodies are most commonly associated with\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/469\">antiphospholipid syndrome</a> which increases the risk of\nthrombosis.</p>\n\n<p>Anticentromere antibodies are associated with limited systemic\nsclerosis.</p>\n\n<p>Myeloperoxidase is the antigen which p-ANCA (antineutrophil\ncytoplasmic antibodies) targets. It is associated with a number of\nvasculitides but most classically microscopic polyangiitis.</p>\n\n<p>Antinuclear antibodies are associated with 80-90% of cases of\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/103\">systemic lupus erythematosus</a> but are also found with Sj\u00f6gren's\nsyndrome, <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/105\">rheumatoid arthritis</a>, <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/130\">autoimmune hepatitis</a>, systemic\nsclerosis, and polymyositis and dermatomyositis.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference:</strong></p>\n\n<ol>\n<li>Hirschfield GM, et al. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19458352\" target=\"_blank\">Primary biliary <span class=\"\" data-bpid=\"278\">cirrhosis</span> associated with HLA,\nIL12A, and IL12RB2 variants</a>. <cite>N Engl J Med.</cite>\n2009;360:2544-55.</li>\n\n<li>Kaplan MM, Gershwin ME. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16177252\" target=\"_blank\">Primary biliary <span class=\"\" data-bpid=\"278\">cirrhosis</span></a>. <cite>N Engl J\nMed.</cite> 2005;353:1261-73.</li>\n</ol></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 38-year-old woman presents with a recent history of pruritus,\nfatigue, and jaundice.</p>\n\n<p>Liver biopsy revealed periportal fibrosis with periportal\ninflammation and prominent enlargement of the portal tracts.</p>\n\n<p>Which one of the following antibodies is most likely to be found\nin the blood?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117655\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117655\"><span>Antimitochondrial</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117653\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117653\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Anticardiolipin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117657\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117657\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antinuclear</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117654\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117654\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Anticentromere</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117656\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80677\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117656\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antimyeloperoxidase</span></div></div>",
        "id": 274
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This woman is likely to have Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome, which is an\nextrahepatic association of hepatitis C.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/234\">Porphyria cutanea tarda</a>, rather than acute intermittent\nporphyria, is associated with hepatitis C. <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/624\">Lichen planus</a>, rather\nthan lichen sclerosis, is another known cutaneous association with\nhepatitis C.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">Hepatitis C</a> is associated with haemotological disease and\nmalignancy. <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/870\">Cryoglobulinaemia</a> (mixed essential type) is the most\nwell-recognised of these with its attendant cutaneous, neurological\nand renal complications.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">Hepatitis C</a> is also associated with myeloma and monoclonal\ngammopathies rather than Waldenstrom's macroglobulinaemia.</p>\n\n<p>Lymphoma, rather than leukaemia, is another extrahepatic\nassociation of hepatitis C.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 35-year-old woman who was diagnosed with hepatitis C six\nmonths ago has attended follow up in the gastroenterology\nclinic.</p>\n\n<p>She reports dry eyes and asks if this could be related to her\nhepatitis C.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is an extrahepatic association of\nhepatitis C?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398094\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199787\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398094\"><span>Sj\u00f6gren's syndrome</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398093\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199787\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398093\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Lichen sclerosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398095\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199787\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398095\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Waldenstrom's macroglobulinaemia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398091\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199787\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398091\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Acute intermittent porphyria</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398092\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199787\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398092\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Leukaemia</span></div></div>",
        "id": 275
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Transferrin saturation</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has a suspected diagnosis of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> as\nsuggested by the presentation and laboratory investigations\nincluding elevated ferritin.</p>\n\n<p>The next investigation would be measurement of transferrin\nsaturation and then if elevated (above 45%) genotyping\n(homozygosity for C282y mutations) would next be considered and\nwould be expected to clinch the diagnosis.</p>\n\n<p>In the event of rarer mutations confirmation with liver biopsy\nmay be required.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old man being investigated for diabetes and impotence\nis noted to have the following results:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>30 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Aspartate aminotransferase</th>\n<td>22 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Fasting plasma glucose</th>\n<td>7.4 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.0-6.0)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Ferritin</th>\n<td>500 \u00b5g/L</td>\n<td>(15-300)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which one of the following would be the next most appropriate\ninvestigation?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117496\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80645\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117496\"><span>Serum transferrin receptors</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117497\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80645\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117497\"><span>Transferrin saturation</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117493\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80645\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117493\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Bone marrow smear and iron stain</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117494\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80645\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117494\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117495\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80645\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117495\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Red cell protoporphyrins</span></div></div>",
        "id": 276
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Grade 1 encephalopathy</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>There are five grades of hepatic encephalopathy:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Features of grade 0 encephalopathy include minimal alterations\nand impairment of executive function.</li>\n\n<li>If patients are drowsy they have at least grade 1\nencephalopathy. Grade 1 encephalopathy is associated with sleep\nabnormalities (typically sleep inversion) and changes to behaviour\nand personality (irritability, poor concentration).</li>\n\n<li>Lethargy, apathy and drowsiness are features of grade 2.</li>\n\n<li>Depressed conscious levels (but rousable) are a feature of\ngrade 3 encephalopathy.</li>\n\n<li>In grade 4 patients are comatose with no response to painful\nstimuli.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Confusion covers a huge range of clinical features and is a\nfairly poor descriptive term. Note in the criteria listed that\ngrade 1 and 2 disease includes inappropriate behaviour and some\ndisorientation to time and place - many people would refer to this\nas confusion. The key feature of increasing encephalopathy is\ndepression of the conscious level.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old man with known alcoholic liver disease is noted by\nthe nursing staff to be confused on the ward. On examination he is\ntachycardic with a heart rate of 100 beats per minute, his blood\npressure is stable at 122/85 mmHg.</p>\n\n<p>He is alert, there is no asterixis but his family who are also\npresent report some change in his mood and behaviour.</p>\n\n<p>Abdominal examination reveals ascites with generalised abdominal\ntenderness.</p>\n\n<p>What is the severity of this patient's hepatic\nencephalopathy?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398048\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199778\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398048\"><span>Grade 2 encephalopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398050\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199778\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398050\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Grade 4 encephalopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398047\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199778\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398047\"><span>Grade 1 encephalopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398049\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199778\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398049\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Grade 3 encephalopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398046\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199778\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398046\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Grade 0 encephalopathy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 277
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Autosomal recessive</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Wilson's disease is a rare autosomal recessive disorder of copper metabolism.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has Wilson's disease which is inherited in an\nautosomal recessive fashion due to a mutation on the long arm of\nchromosome 13, characterised by excessive hepatic copper\ndeposition. <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">Cirrhosis</a> is the most common initial presentation.</p>\n\n<p>Kaiser-Fleischer rings occur in 90% of patients but may also\noccur in chronic cholestatic disease.</p>\n\n<p>There are also neuropsychiatric, musculoskeletal,\nhaematological, and renal features.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 20-year-old male presents with bleeding oesophageal\nvarices.</p>\n\n<p>On examination, he has Kayser-Fleischer rings in the cornea.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the inheritance of this disorder?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117886\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80723\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117886\"><span>X linked dominant</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117883\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80723\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117883\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Autosomal dominant</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117884\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80723\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117884\"><span>Autosomal recessive</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117887\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80723\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117887\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Polygenic inheritance</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117885\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80723\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117885\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">X linked recessive</span></div></div>",
        "id": 278
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Blood film</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient is anaemic and his ethnic origin raises the\npossibility of sickle cell disease.</p>\n\n<p>The blood results reveal a mild jaundice with a slightly raised\nalkaline phosphatase. The latter may be explained either by the\npresence of gallstones and irritation of the bile ducts or release\nfrom a bony source (such as in a bone crisis). Gallstones are\ncommon in sickle cell disease due to chronic haemolysis. The\nabsence of dilated bile ducts on ultrasound counts against\ngallstone disease as the underlying pathology.</p>\n\n<p>The elevated lactate dehydrongenase is suggestive of active\nhaemolysis. A sickle cell crisis with haemolysis must be considered\nthe likely cause of the jaundice; this will be best proven on a\nblood film which would show red cell fragments and sickle\ncells.</p>\n\n<p>A split bilirubin would help determine whether the jaundice was\nprehepatic or hepatic/cholestatic however it would not elucidate\nthe underlying cause.</p>\n\n<p>MRCP would be useful in this situation if there were a higher\nindex of clinical suspicion of a ductal gallstone.</p>\n\n<p>Liver biopsy with Perl's staining for iron would be useful\nfor the diagnosis of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a>, although there is\nbiochemical evidence of iron overload; this is most likely\nexplained in this case by repeated transfusion. <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">Haemochromatosis</a>\nwould also be unlikely to give rise to this clinical or biochemical\npicture.</p>\n\n<p>The clinical presentation and liver panel are inconsistent with\na viral hepatitis causing the jaundice though it may be coexistent,\nparticularly in a patient from this area of the world.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 23-year-old man of Gambian origin is admitted to hospital\ncomplaining of severe abdominal and back pain.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is jaundiced without signs of chronic liver\ndisease.</p>\n\n<p>His blood tests reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>98 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>8.9 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>126 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Lactate dehydrogenase</th>\n<td>514 IU/L</td>\n<td>(10-250)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>47 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>140 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>57 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>38 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.1</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>The transferrin saturation is raised at 52%. Abdominal\nultrasound reveals multiple stones in the gallbladder, which is\nthick-walled with no evidence of oedema or pericholecystic fluid,\nand a common bile duct with a diameter of 7 mm without intrahepatic\nduct dilatation.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following investigations is most likely to\nestablish the underlying cause of his jaundice?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398304\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199829\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398304\"><span>Split direct and indirect serum bilirubin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398302\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199829\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398302\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy with Perl's staining</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398305\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199829\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398305\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Viral hepatitis serology</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398301\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199829\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398301\"><span>Blood film</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398303\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199829\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398303\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)</span></div></div>",
        "id": 279
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Blood glucose</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Wernicke's encephalopathy is the most likely diagnosis given\nthe history and examination findings on a background of likely\nalcoholism.</p>\n\n<p>Although all of the above investigations may need to be\nconsidered to exclude other contributing aetiologies to her\npresentation, only the blood glucose can be done quickly and\ncheaply at the bedside.</p>\n\n<p>Hypoglycaemia may have precipitated her deterioration and a\nfinger-prick blood glucose estimation should be the first\ninvestigation.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old widow presents with a one week history of\nprogressive confusion and unsteady gait. She works as a barmaid and\nlives in poor social circumstances.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is malnourished and disorientated. She has\nnystagmus and is unable to abduct either eye. The pupils are\nsluggish and unequal. Ankle jerks are absent but upper limb\nreflexes are present.</p>\n\n<p>Shortly after her admission you are called to the ward as she\nhas become very drowsy and has collapsed on the floor.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations on admission showed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>114 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>99 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White blood cells</th>\n<td>5.6 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>230 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>129 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>3.2 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>27 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum gamma glutamyl transferase</th>\n<td>440 U/L</td>\n<td>(4-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>180 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate aminotransferase</th>\n<td>90 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>45 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum albumin</th>\n<td>33 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Prothrombin time</th>\n<td>12 secs</td>\n<td>(11.5-15.5)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following should be the first investigation?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117481\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80642\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117481\"><span>Blood cultures</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117479\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80642\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117479\"><span>Blood glucose</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117480\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80642\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117480\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">EEG</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117478\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80642\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117478\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">CT head</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117482\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80642\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117482\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">B12 and folate levels</span></div></div>",
        "id": 280
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>It is catalysed by a glucuronyl transferase</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Bilirubin conjugation is catalysed by a glucuronyl transferase.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>In <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1151\">Dubin-Johnson syndrome</a> conjugation is normal, but excretion\nfrom the hepatocyte into the bile is impaired, resulting in a\nconjugated bilirubinaemia.</p>\n\n<p>Sodium valproate is an enzyme inhibitor.</p>\n\n<p>Rifampicin is an enzyme inducer.</p>\n\n<p>Bilirubin is conjugated in the hepatocytes.</p>\n\n<p>In both Gilbert's and Crigler-Najjar syndrome there is an\nimpairment of UDP glucuronosyltransferase. In Crigler-Najjar levels\nare extremely low (undetectable in type 1 and &lt;10% in type 2),\nwhereas in Gilbert's levels are less significantly reduced.\nBoth are associated with an unconjugated bilirubinaemia.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>Which of the following concerning the conjugation of bilirubin\nis correct?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117357\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80617\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117357\"><span>It occurs in the Kupfer cells of the liver</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117353\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80617\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117353\"><span>It is catalysed by a glucuronyl transferase</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117356\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80617\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117356\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">It is inhibited by rifampicin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117355\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80617\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117355\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">It is increased by valproate</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117354\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80617\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117354\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">It is impaired in Dubin-Johnson syndrome</span></div></div>",
        "id": 281
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Flare of chronic hepatitis B</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>In areas of low HBV prevalence, such as the United Kingdom, a\ncombination of HBsAg positivity and features of acute hepatitis\nusually indicates acute self-limiting <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> infection.</p>\n\n<p>In countries with high prevalence of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a>, the majority\nof infection is acquired vertically during childhood and leads to\nchronicity rather than acute infection.</p>\n\n<p>Where there is an intermediate or high level of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a>\nprevalence, flares of chronic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> and acute self-limiting\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> are often mutually misdiagnosed where an\nindividual's <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> status is unknown prior to the current\nillness. It is frequently very difficult to make the distinction,\nespecially on the basis of a single assessment without knowledge of\nthe course of the episode.</p>\n\n<p>Chronic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> is defined by the presence of HBsAg in the\nserum for more than six months. HBeAg in the serum is present in\nacute infection and may persist in chronic for several years.</p>\n\n<p>In chronic infection eAg, seroconversion marks a change from the\nimmune tolerance to immune control phase of the disease.</p>\n\n<p>HBeAg presence cannot be used to distinguish between acute HBV\nor a flare of chronic disease.</p>\n\n<p>Anti-HBc-IgM is typically found in acute HBV infection, however\nit can be found in 10-15% of patients with chronic HBV. This is\nespecially true when considering acute flares of chronic hepatitis.\nThe sensitivity and specificity for HBc-IgM to distinguish between\nacute HBV and a chronic flare has been reported as low as 77% and\n70% respectively. Using high titres to determine cut-offs (1:10,000\nor greater) does improve this significantly however.</p>\n\n<p>Flares of chronic HBV are typically associated with higher\nlevels of HBV DNA and AFP than acute self-limiting disease.\nAdditionally flares of chronic HBV tend to be associated with less\nnecroinflammation, and thus ALT tends to be as raised as in acute\nHBV, but hepatic synthetic dysfunction is more common.</p>\n\n<p>In this case, the patient originates from an area of the world\nwith a high prevalence of HBV infection. Additionally, there is\nclearly a strong family history of liver disease which, given the\nclinical context, is highly likely to be attributable to HBV\ninfection. No risk factors for the acquisition of HBV acutely are\ndescribed. The combination of these factors with the significantly\nraised AFP and relatively modest elevation of the ALT with marked\njaundice would tend to favour a diagnosis of a flare of chronic HBV\nover acute HBV despite low titre anti-HBc-IgM titre.</p>\n\n<p>The alanine aminotransferase (ALT) is too high for\nalcohol-related hepatitis.</p>\n\n<p>The alpha-fetoprotein is commonly elevated during acute\nhepatitis due to hepatic regeneration.</p>\n\n<p>HCC is unlikely in a 27-year-old and would not account for the\nraised ALT.</p>\n\n<p>Hepatitis E is not endemic in the United Kingdom and is a very\nunlikely diagnosis.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 27-year-old refugee from Cambodia presents with a short\nhistory of fatigue and jaundice. He has lived in the United Kingdom\nfor the last 12 months.</p>\n\n<p>His mother died of liver disease age 55 and his older brother\ndied of liver cancer three years previously in Cambodia age 40. His\nbrother was known to have hepatitis B.</p>\n\n<p>He consumes 30-40 units of alcohol a week.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>145 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>WBC</th>\n<td>7.6 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>156 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>213 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum gamma glutamyl transferase</th>\n<td>200 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>150 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate aminotransferase</th>\n<td>912 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>1450 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alpha-fetoprotein</th>\n<td>45 kU/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>HBsAg</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Positive</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>HBeAg</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Positive</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti-HBc (IgM)</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Positive</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti-HAV (IgM)</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Negative</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti-HAV (IgG)</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Positive</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti-HCV</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Negative</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>An ultrasound scan of his liver shows mild hepatomegaly and an\nechogenic liver but no other abnormality.</p>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117477\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80641\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117477\"><span>Hepatocellular cancer (HCC)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117473\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80641\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117473\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Acute hepatitis B</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117474\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80641\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117474\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcohol related hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117475\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80641\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117475\"><span>Flare of chronic hepatitis B</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117476\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80641\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117476\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis E</span></div></div>",
        "id": 282
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>It may be associated with keratoconjunctivitis sicca</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>It occurs frequently in young (10-20 years) and middle-aged\nwomen.</p>\n\n<p>Twenty five per cent present as acute hepatitis but usually the\nonset is insidious. Some may be asymptomatic for years and then are\nfound to have signs of chronic liver disease.</p>\n\n<p>Amenorrhoea is common. It is associated with hyperglobulinaemia\nand other autoimmmune disease.</p>\n\n<p>Sixty per cent are associated with HLA-B8, DR3 and Dw3.</p>\n\n<p>The sicca syndrome (xerostomia/dry eyes, keratoconjunctivitis\nsicca) may occur.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>Which of the following statements is true of autoimmune\nhepatitis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117611\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80668\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117611\"><span>It is associated with hypogammaglobulinaemia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117609\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80668\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117609\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">It rarely presents before 20 years of age</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117608\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80668\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117608\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">It usually presents as an acute hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117610\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80668\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117610\"><span>It may be associated with keratoconjunctivitis sicca</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117612\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80668\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117612\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">It rarely interferes with menstruation except in later stages</span></div></div>",
        "id": 283
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Arrange for DNA analysis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This man is likely to have hereditary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a>\n(HHC).</p>\n\n<p>Haemachromatosis is caused by dysregulated iron homeostatis due\nto inappropriate increased iron absorption in the duodenum and\nproximal small intestine.</p>\n\n<p>It is an autosomal recessive hereditary condition which is\nassociated with homozygous C282Y mutation of the HFE gene in North\nEuropeans.</p>\n\n<p>Increased absorption of iron results in its deposition in the\norgans, notably the liver, pancreas, heart, joints, skin, and\npituitary. This causes <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a>, restrictive cardiomyopathy,\ndiabetes mellitus, arthropathy, skin hyperpigmentation, and gonadal\nfailure. Males and females are affected equally but females are\noften 'protected' from the clinical features by menstrual\nblood loss.</p>\n\n<p>Arthropathy is relatively common. It is chronic and progressive\nand mildly inflammatory. There is a predilection for the\nmetacarpophalangeal joints and is often accompanied by\nchondrocalcinosis. Iron load is probably a major determinant, but\nit does not usually respond to venesection.</p>\n\n<p>Early diagnosis and treatment is critical in <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> as\nsurvival and morbidity are improved if phlebotomy is initiated\nprior to the development of cirrhosis.</p>\n\n<p>Transferrin saturation is suggested as the initial screening\ntest: a level of more than 45% warrants further investigation (less\nthan 45% usually excludes the diagnosis). Genetic screening is then\nperformed. If the usual C282Y HFE mutation is found this makes the\ndiagnosis.</p>\n\n<p>Ferritin is measured to help guide further investigation and\ntreatment: if more than 1000, a liver biopsy should be performed\nand treatment initiated. If the ferritin is within normal range and\nthe liver function tests are normal, patients can be followed\nclosely.&nbsp; If the C282Y HFE mutation is not present other genotypes\nshould be looked for and if present a liver biopsy is\nindicated.</p>\n\n<p>The goal of therapy is to remove excess body iron stores which\nis commonly done via phlebotomy. Initially this is weekly or twice\nweekly (if tolerated) venesections of 500 cm<sup>3</sup> until the\nserum ferritin is less than 50 ng/mL. Transferritin saturation\nshould also be reduced to less than 50% if possible. After these\ngoals are reached maintenance therapy is typically required three\nto four times per year.</p>\n\n<p>The diagnosis of haemachromatosis should obviously be made\nbefore you initiate such treatment. When iron overload and anaemia\nare present concomitantly chelation with desferoxamine may be\nrequired. Patients should be told to avoid vitamin C\nsupplementation as this can enhance iron toxicity.</p>\n\n<p>End stage liver disease, portal hypertension, and hepatocellular\ncarcinoma (which is increased up to 200-fold) may necessitate liver\ntransplantation. This is associated with poorer outcome compared\nwith other indications because of increased incidence of infection\nand cardiac complications.</p>\n\n<p>A liver biopsy is not required to make the diagnosis of HHC\nalthough may be indicated for prognostic reasons if <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> is\nsuspected.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 46-year-old man with a family history of haemochromatosis\npresented to outpatients for advice.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations revealed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Serum ferritin</th>\n<td>453 \u00b5g/L</td>\n<td>(15-300)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum iron</th>\n<td>29 mol/L</td>\n<td>(12-30)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum iron binding capacity</th>\n<td>46 mol/L</td>\n<td>(45-75)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Transferrin saturation</th>\n<td>63%</td>\n<td>(20-50)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the most appropriate next step in management?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117360\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80618\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117360\"><span>Monitor his serum ferritin regularly</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117361\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80618\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117361\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Take no action unless the iron saturation exceeds 90%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117359\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80618\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117359\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Begin a venesection programme</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117358\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80618\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117358\"><span>Arrange for DNA analysis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117362\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80618\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117362\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Undertake a liver biopsy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 284
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Raised free serum copper</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Wilson's disease typically causes:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>reduced caeruloplasmin</li>\n\n<li>raised urinary copper, and</li>\n\n<li>raised free serum copper.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> typically causes a positive\nanti-mitochondrial antibody.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Further Reading:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Medicine Plus. <a href=\"http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/wilsondisease.html\" target=\"_blank\">Wilson Disease.</a></p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old man is diagnosed with Wilson's disease.</p>\n\n<p>You are trying to make sense of his blood test results.</p>\n\n<p>Which one of the following would you expect to find in a patient\nwith Wilson's disease?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"200993\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129812\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"200993\"><span>Hypercalcaemia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"200996\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129812\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"200996\"><span>Raised free serum copper</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"200995\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129812\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"200995\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Raised caeruloplasmin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"200997\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129812\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"200997\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Reduced urinary copper</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"200994\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129812\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"200994\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Positive anti-mitochondrial antibody</span></div></div>",
        "id": 285
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Portal vein thrombosis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The diagnosis is portal vein thrombosis which can be secondary\nto pancreatitis as seems likely in this man's case.</p>\n\n<p>The portal vein is expanded and contains thrombus (the\nnon-enhancing vessel).</p>\n\n<p>There are associated wedge defects within the liver consistent\nwith either perfusion defects or infarcts.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old male is admitted with fever and acute abdominal\npain.</p>\n\n<p>Over the last three days he has developed&nbsp; increasing abdominal\nswelling and a low grade fever.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he has right upper quadrant pain with two finger\nbreadth hepatomegaly and he has shifting dullness. His radiology is\nillustrated.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"asset/55.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"221\"></p>\n\n<p>Which of the following options is the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118019\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80750\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118019\"><span>Focal fatty sparing</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118021\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80750\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118021\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Pancreatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118018\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80750\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118018\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Amoebic abscess</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118020\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80750\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118020\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatocellular carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118022\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80750\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118022\"><span>Portal vein thrombosis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 286
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Guided liver biopsy and aspiration</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This lady has a pyogenic hepatic abscess as shown on the CT\nscan. This is supported by the:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>evated temperature</li>\n\n<li>CRP decreased albumin</li>\n\n<li>elevated alkaline phosphatase, and</li>\n\n<li>tender liver.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Given her breast history these findings may point to metastatic\ncarcinoma but the CT shows otherwise. A blood culture is positive\nin 50% of cases and is likely to be most helpful. Aspiration and\ndrainage are important for both identification of the aetiological\norganism and treatment of the abscess (in conjunction with\nantibiotics).</p>\n\n<p>The other investigations are mainly aimed at the investigation\nof malignant disease. Sources can be gastrointestingal tract and\ngiven left iliac fossa symptoms and altered bowels, diverticular\ninfection may be the cause.</p>\n\n<p>Liver abscesses are often fatal if untreated.</p>\n\n<p>Imaging appearances are not consistent with a hydatid cyst,\nthese usually have a clearly delineated wall, are fluid filled and\nmay demonstrate some calcification.</p>\n\n<p>Internal septae delineating daughter cysts may be present.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 68-year-old lady was referred to the out patient clinic by her\ngeneral practitioner.</p>\n\n<p>She had experienced 2 kg of unplanned weight loss in two months.\nHer appetite was decreased. On direct questioning she admitted to\nfeeling low in mood after the recent death of her husband.</p>\n\n<p>There was alteration of her bowel habit with worsening\nconstipation and occasional fresh blood passed per rectum. She\ncomplained of a vague discomfort in the left iliac fossa. She had a\npast history of carcinoma of the left breast ten years previously.\nShe was an ex-smoker having given up fifteen years ago, she did not\nconsume alcohol. She did not take any regular prescribed\nmedications, but took over-the-counter analgesia for her abdominal\ndiscomfort.</p>\n\n<p>On examination, she appeared thin. She was not clinically\nanaemic. Pulse was 80 beats per minute with blood pressure 115/65\nmmHg and she had a temperature of 38\u00b0C. Heart sounds were normal.\nChest was clear. Examination of the breast confirmed a left total\nmastectomy, no masses palpable. Abdominal examination revealed a\npalpable liver edge 3 cm below the right costal margin, it was\nsomewhat tender. There was mild tenderness in the left iliac fossa,\nbut no mass.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations revealed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>109 g/L</td>\n<td>(115 - 165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White blood cells</th>\n<td>15.5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4 - 11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>600 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150 - 400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum C reactive protein</th>\n<td>100 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum albumin</th>\n<td>28 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum AST</th>\n<td>36 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>220 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>A CT scan of the abdomen was performed. An image from this study\nis shown below:</p>\n\n<p><script type=\"text/javascript\" src=\"/Shared/JavaScript/ddpowerzoomer.js\"></script><script type=\"text/javascript\">jQuery(document).ready(function($) {$(\"img[id^=146]\").addpowerzoom( { magnifiersize: [150, 150], largeimage: 'https://media.onexamination.com/MediaBrowser/zoomify/146.jpg' } );});</script><img id=\"146\" src=\"asset/56.png\"></p>\n\n<p>Which would be most appropriate initial investigation?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118114\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118114\"><span>Chest x ray</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118116\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118116\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Mammogram</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118117\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118117\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Upper and lower gastrointestinal endoscopy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118113\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118113\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hydatid serology</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118115\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80769\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118115\"><span>Guided liver biopsy and aspiration</span></div></div>",
        "id": 287
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>50%</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>An episode of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/793\">spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</a> carries a two\nyear mortality rate of 50%.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old male with alcoholic cirrhosis and ascites presents\nwith a three day history of abdominal pain.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is febrile with a temperature of 38\u00b0C, he is\ntachycardic with a heart rate of 112 beats per minute, and his\nblood pressure is maintained at 125/80 mmHg. He has generalised\nabdominal tenderness, there is no asterixis.</p>\n\n<p>You perform an ascitic tap and the neutrophil count is\n320/microL confirming a diagnosis of spontaneous bacterial\nperitonitis.</p>\n\n<p>What is the two year mortality rate of spontaneous bacterial\nperitonitis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398104\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199789\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398104\"><span>70%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398102\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199789\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398102\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">20%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398101\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199789\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398101\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">10%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398103\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199789\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398103\"><span>50%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398105\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199789\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398105\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">80%</span></div></div>",
        "id": 288
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Intravenous cefotaxime</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This lady has <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/793\">spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</a> as suggested by\nthe typical history, ascites, and raised polymorphonuclear count\nwithin the ascitic tap.</p>\n\n<p>It is most commonly seen in alcoholic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> and the\ncausative organisms are usually <em><em>Escherichia coli</em>,</em>\n<em>Klebsiella</em>, <em>S. pneumoniae</em> or\n<em>Enterococci</em>. (Compare this with the mixed growth seen in\nother forms of peritonitis).</p>\n\n<p>Sending some ascitic fluid in blood culture bottles increases\nthe yield.</p>\n\n<p>Initial treatment is with broad spectrum antibiotics such as\ncefotaxime.</p>\n\n<p>Norfloxacin is recommended for short term prophylaxis.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 35-year-old woman with alcoholic cirrhosis is admitted with\ndeteriorating encephalopathy and abdominal discomfort. An ascitic\ntap revealed a polymorphonuclear cell count of 350 cells per\nmm<sup>3</sup>.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most appropriate therapy?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117717\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80689\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117717\"><span>Oral neomycin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117716\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80689\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117716\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Intravenous metronidazole</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117713\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80689\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117713\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Oral norfloxacin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117714\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80689\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117714\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Intravenous amoxicillin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117715\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80689\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117715\"><span>Intravenous cefotaxime</span></div></div>",
        "id": 289
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary biliary cirrhosis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>primary biliary cirrhosis presents with tiredness and itching, in association with clinical (splenomegaly) and biochemical (pancytopenia) evidence of portal hypertension</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The presentation with tiredness and itching, in association\nclinical (splenomegaly) and biochemical (pancytopenia) evidence of\nportal hypertension is suggestive of primary biliary cirrhosis. The\nfindings of a generalised increase in pigmentation and the\nobstructive picture demonstrated on the liver panel (alkaline\nphosphatase raised in excess of transasminases) are also highly\nsuggestive.</p>\n\n<p>Addison's disease is a highly unlikely diagnosis given that\nthere has been no change in control of the lady's hypertension\nor glycaemic control, additionally itching is not a presenting\nfeature.&nbsp;Addisons disease tends to present with hypotension and a\npostural drop. Not hypertension. Other findings such as pruritis,\npancytopenia, deranged LFTs, splenomegaly etc. Do not fit Addisons\ndisease.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Hypothyroidism may present with both itching and tiredness,\nhowever it is not associated with splenomegaly and portal\nhypertension.</p>\n\n<p>The thyroid function tests here demonstrate only a borderline\nelevation of the TSH.</p>\n\n<p>Lymphoma may also present with tiredness and itching however\nnight sweats and fevers are more common and one might expect to\nfind lymphadenopathy on examination in addition to features such as\nan elevated serum lactate dehydrogenase.</p>\n\n<p>An iron deficiency anaemia may produce generalised pruritus\nhowever although this patient is anaemic the ferritin is within the\nnormal range as is the mean corpuscular volume making iron\ndeficiency less likely.</p>\n\n<p>The mild neutropaenia is probably secondary to the splenomegally\n(sequestering of white blood cells). Malabsorption and anaemia of\nchronic disease could account for the mild anaemia. Immune mediated\nplatelet destruction and splenic pooling of platelets may both play\na part in the thrombocytopaenia observed in primary biliary\ncirrhosis.&nbsp;</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 41-year-old lady presents with tiredness and itching. The\nsymptoms have come on gradually over several months but have become\nalmost unbearable in recent weeks.</p>\n\n<p>She suffers with hypertension and was diagnosed with diabetes at\nthe age of 13. She reports that both her hypertension and diabetes\nhave been well controlled recently. She is currently taking Lantus,\nNovoRapid, lisinopril and simvastatin.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there is evidence of widespread excoriation and\nsome hyperpigmentation. There is no evidence of fluid overload.\nAbdominal examination reveals mild splenomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Blood tests reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>106 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Mean corpuscular volume</th>\n<td>83 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>3.1 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>35 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Ferritin</th>\n<td>15 \u00b5g/L</td>\n<td>(15-300)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>24 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>29 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>43 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>298 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Sodium</th>\n<td>132 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Potassium</th>\n<td>5.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>8.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>87 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Lactate dehydrogenase</th>\n<td>350 IU/L</td>\n<td>(10-250)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Thyroid stimulating hormone</th>\n<td>4.8 mU/L</td>\n<td>(0.4-5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Thyroxine</th>\n<td>13 pmol/L</td>\n<td>(10-22)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>What is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398439\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199856\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398439\"><span>Lymphoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398436\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199856\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398436\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Addison's disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398437\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199856\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398437\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hypothyroidism</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398440\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199856\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398440\"><span>Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398438\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199856\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398438\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Iron deficiency anaemia</span></div></div>",
        "id": 290
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Flumazenil</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The dramatic decline in conscious level associated with\ninstitution of an aggressive alcohol detoxification regimen in a\npatient with impaired hepatic function (therefore reduced hepatic\nclearance) makes benzodiazepine toxicity the most likely\ndiagnosis.</p>\n\n<p>The rapid detoxification programmes now used are excellent for\nacute withdrawal from alcohol but should not be used in patients\nwho are encephalopathic (as suggested by his confusion and flapping\ntremor).</p>\n\n<p>Flumazenil reverses the effects of benzodiazepines, but care\nmust taken in its usage due to a relatively short half life when\ncompared to benzodiazepines and the risk of provoking seizures when\nadministered.</p>\n\n<p>Causes of his encephalopathy should be sought, for example,\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/793\">spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</a>, GI bleed, or infection.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 55-year-old male previously diagnosed with alcoholic liver\ndisease was admitted with increasing confusion. He consumed at\nleast 40 units of alcohol weekly.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he was confused with a Glasgow coma scale of 14\nand had a slight flap of the outstretched hands. His temperature\nwas 36.8\u00b0C and he had a blood pressure of 122/88 mmHg. He was noted\nto be jaundiced with spider naevi and palmar erythema. Abdominal\nexamination revealed slight distension but no organomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations revealed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>139 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>3.6 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>2.7 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum creatinine</th>\n<td>65 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>65 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum aspartate aminotransferase</th>\n<td>150 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>110 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>450 U/L</td>\n<td>(30-100)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum gamma glutamyl transferase</th>\n<td>500 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>At that stage he was commenced on the rapid detoxification\nprogramme consisting of diazepam 20 mg at a minimum interval of two\nhourly (maximum dose 200 mg on 24 hours, standard regime). The\nfollowing day, he was found collapsed in the bathroom on ward.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following agents is administered is most likely to\nlead to an improvement in his conscious level?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117392\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80624\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117392\"><span>Vitamin K</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117390\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80624\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117390\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Naloxone</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117389\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80624\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117389\"><span>Flumazenil</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117391\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80624\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117391\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Thiamine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117388\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80624\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117388\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cefotaxime</span></div></div>",
        "id": 291
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Uncooperative patient</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>An uncooperative patient is a contraindication to performing a\nliver biopsy as sudden movement can result in laceration to the\nliver.</p>\n\n<p>Anti-platelet medication should be stopped for at least one week\nprior to liver biopsy.</p>\n\n<p>Significant volume ascites is a contraindication to percutaneous\nliver biopsy but a transjugular biopsy can be performed as an\nalternative.</p>\n\n<p>For percutaneous biopsy ascites should be drained first.\nPercutaneous liver biopsy should be avoided if the INR is greater\nthan 1.3 (prothrombin time greater than three seconds above\nnormal). If the INR is &gt;1.4, fresh frozen plasma (FFP) may be\nadministered and liver biopsy then carried out if the INR is less\nthan 1.4.</p>\n\n<p>The minimum safe lower limit of platelets is 60. Where the\nplatelet count is 40-60 biopsy can be performed immediately after\nplatelet transfusion provided there has been an increment to the\nrecommended level.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 22-year-old woman presents with a one week history of\njaundice. She has no past medical history. There is no travel\nhistory and she denies a family history of liver disease.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there are no stigmata of chronic liver disease.\nShe is not encephalopathic; she has mild right upper quadrant\ntenderness on abdominal examination.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood results are as follows:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Hb</th>\n<td>130 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>70 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.3</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>1256 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>406 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>32 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound scan demonstrates features of acute\nhepatitis. The team plan a liver biopsy.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is a contraindication to liver\nbiopsy?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398024\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398024\"><span>Platelets 70</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398025\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398025\"><span>Uncooperative patient</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398021\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398021\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Antiplatelet therapy which has been stopped for 10 days</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398022\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398022\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Drained ascites</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398023\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199773\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398023\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">INR 1.3</span></div></div>",
        "id": 292
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Starvation</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Starvation (or severe malnutrition or dieting) is a risk factor\nfor the development of non-alcoholic fatty liver disease.</p>\n\n<p>The most common association with fatty liver disease is\nmetabolic syndrome.</p>\n\n<p>Other factors may contribute to fatty liver disease, such\nas:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>drugs (for example, amiodarone, methotrexate)</li>\n\n<li>alcohol</li>\n\n<li>metabolic abnormalities (for example, &nbsp;galactosaemia, glycogen\nstorage diseases), and</li>\n\n<li>nutritional status (for example, overnutrition, total\nparenteral nutrition).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old woman is incidentally found to have abnormal liver\nfunction tests.</p>\n\n<p>There is no history of high alcohol intake and she has no past\nmedical history. There is no family history of liver disease.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there are no stigmata of chronic liver disease\nbut she has a palpable liver 3 cm below the right costal\nmargin.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood results are as follows:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Hb</th>\n<td>130 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>94 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>WBC</th>\n<td>5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>200 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>CRP</th>\n<td>10 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bil</th>\n<td>15 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>310 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>130 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>260 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>GGT</th>\n<td>100 U/L</td>\n<td>(4-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>37 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound scan is reported as showing a fatty\nliver.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is a risk factor for non-alcoholic fatty\nliver disease?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398134\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199795\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398134\"><span>Starvation</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398133\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199795\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398133\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Low triglyceride level</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398131\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199795\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398131\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gastric surgery</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398132\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199795\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398132\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Low body mass index</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398135\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199795\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398135\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Young male</span></div></div>",
        "id": 293
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Intravenous antibiotics</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>An ascitic neutrophil count of &gt;250/mm3 is indicative of spontaneous bacterial peritonitis which should be treated with IV antibiotics. </li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This man has <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/793\">spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</a> (SBP).</p>\n\n<p>Appropriate treatment is IV antibiotics.</p>\n\n<p>He is likely to have a decreased intravascular volume and\nrequire IV albumin as volume expansion.</p>\n\n<p>Fluid restriction, diuretics, or large volume paracentesis are\nlikely to cause further hypovolaemia and precipitate renal\nfailure.</p>\n\n<p>There is no stated indication for a TIPSS, indications are:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>diuretic resistant ascites</li>\n\n<li>intractable portal hypertensive bleeding, and</li>\n\n<li>hepato-renal failure.</li>\n</ul></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 63-year-old patient with known alcohol related cirrhosis\npresented with ascites, abdominal tenderness, and peripheral\noedema.</p>\n\n<p>A diagnostic tap revealed a neutrophil count of\n400/mm<sup>3</sup> (&lt;250/mm<sup>3</sup>).</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following would be of most immediate benefit?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117351\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80616\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117351\"><span>Therapeutic paracentesis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117352\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80616\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117352\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Trans-jugular intrahepatic porto-systemic shunt</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117348\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80616\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117348\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Fluid restriction and a no added salt diet</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117350\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80616\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117350\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Oral spironolactone</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117349\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80616\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117349\"><span>Intravenous antibiotics</span></div></div>",
        "id": 294
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Perforated bowel</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This man has very bloody ascites with a significantly elevated,\nneutrophilic white cell count.</p>\n\n<p>The degree of neutrophilia and presence of organisms on the Gram\nstain indicate an acute infection. The polymicrobial nature of this\ninfection makes perforated abdominal viscera the most likely\ndiagnosis.</p>\n\n<p>The presence of signs of chronic liver disease and a high serum\nascites albumin gradient (&gt;11 g/L) indicate underlying portal\nhypertension which is a likely underlying cause for the presence of\nascites.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/793\">Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</a> is usually the result of\ninfection with a single organism, almost invariably Gram\nnegative.</p>\n\n<p>The liver function tests in this case are not suggestive of\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/345\">ascending cholangitis</a> (normal alkaline phosphatase) and are more\nsuggestive of alcohol related liver disease (AST:ALT ratio\n&gt;2:1), additionally it is usually caused by a single organism\nand not complicated by the presence of ascites.</p>\n\n<p>Whilst the blood tests are suggestive of a degree of alcoholic\nhepatitis this does not explain the presence of significant bloody\nascites with a polymicrobial infection.</p>\n\n<p>Whilst the evidence of chronic liver disease and the elevated\nserum ascites albumin gradient indicates that <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> and portal\nhypertension are the causes of ascites the markedly elevated cell\ncounts and presence of multiple organisms on the Gram stain\nindicate that this cannot explain all of the current\npresentation.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 43-year-old man with known chronic liver disease secondary to\nalcohol is admitted with abdominal pain and jaundice.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is jaundiced and a little drowsy with a\ndistended abdomen demonstrating shifting dullness and tenderness in\nthe right upper quadrant.</p>\n\n<p>His blood tests show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>112 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">White cell count</th>\n<td>22.3 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">Platelets</th>\n<td>45 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">Sodium</th>\n<td>131 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">Potassium</th>\n<td>4.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">Urea</th>\n<td>13.4 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">Creatinine</th>\n<td>143 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">Bilirubin</th>\n<td>47 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">ALT</th>\n<td>65 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">AST</th>\n<td>178 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">ALP</th>\n<td>127 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">Albumin</th>\n<td>28 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th scope=\"row\">INR</th>\n<td>1.4</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>An ascitic tap is performed and bloody fluid is aspirated from\nthe abdominal cavity. Analysis of the fluid reveals:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Red cell count</th>\n<td>21,385/mm<sup>3</sup></td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th rowspan=\"2\">White cell count</th>\n<td>6,734/mm<sup>3</sup></td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td>90% neutrophils</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>15 g/L</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>A Gram stain reveals Gram negative bacilli and Gram positive\ncocci.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely underlying diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398351\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199839\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398351\"><span>Alcoholic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398352\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199839\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398352\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ascending cholangitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398353\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199839\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398353\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398354\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199839\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398354\"><span>Perforated bowel</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398355\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199839\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398355\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 295
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Genetic analysis for C282Y and H63D mutations</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The patient has haemochromatosis. The skin appears tanned, he is\nimpotent (hypogonadal), and has diabetes. There is an elevated\nlevel of iron and transferrin saturation is high.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">Haemochromatosis</a> is an autosomal recessive condition.</p>\n\n<p>Two mutations of the HFE gene (C282Y and H63D) account for over\n90% of cases in Europeans.</p>\n\n<p>The disease is also associated with HLA-A3 and HLA-B14.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 52-year-old man with newly diagnosed diabetes is referred to\nthe diabetes clinic.</p>\n\n<p>He gave a two month history of polyuria and polydipsia and his\nurine tested positive for glucose in the GP surgery after returning\nfrom holiday in Portugal.</p>\n\n<p>He has no past history of note and was not taking any regular\nmedication although he had requested a trial of sildenafil from his\nGP for recent onset of erectile dysfunction.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he appears tanned and well. A liver edge is\npalpable 2 cm below the right costal margin and his testes are\nfound to be small.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>151 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White blood cells</th>\n<td>7.2 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>341 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum iron</th>\n<td>50 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(12-30)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Transferrin saturation</th>\n<td>85%</td>\n<td>(&lt;50%)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urinalysis:</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Glucose +</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which investigation is most likely to assist in making a\ndiagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118182\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118182\"><span>Ultrasound scan of the abdomen</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118181\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118181\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Total iron binding capacity (TIBC)</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118180\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118180\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Serum ferritin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118178\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118178\"><span>Genetic analysis for C282Y and H63D mutations</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118179\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118179\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Red cell transketolase</span></div></div>",
        "id": 296
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Wernicke's encephalopathy</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Wernicke's encephalopathy is a result of thiamine\ndeficiency. Most cases occur in those with a history of chronic\nalcohol ingestion however malnutrition of any cause is a risk\nfactor. The classic triad of features is</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Encephalopathy</li>\n\n<li>Ataxia and</li>\n\n<li>Oculomotor dysfunction (usually nystagmus but also potentially\nlateral rectus palsies or conjugate gaze palsies).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/712\">Normal pressure hydrocephalus</a> is a potentially reversible cause\nof dementia. Cognitive decline is associated with an ataxic gait\nand early onset of urinary incontinence. Clouding of consciousness\nand nystagmus are not features and the history is usually\nprogressive and chronic rather than acute.</p>\n\n<p>Korsakoff's psychosis is a chronic condition resulting from\nuntreated thiamine deficiency and is characterised by both\nanterograde and retrograde amnesia with confabulation.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/549\">Alcohol withdrawal</a> may involve some of the features described\nabove (for example, inattentiveness, confusion) however it is\nusually typified by psychomotor agitation and sympathetic\nsymptoms.</p>\n\n<p>It is likely that a <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/416\">subdural haematoma</a> would need to be excluded\nin a patient such as this however the presence of nystagmus and\nataxia make a diagnosis of Wernicke's more likely.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old woman is admitted to hospital with hypothermia\nhaving been found on the street.</p>\n\n<p>A blood ethanol level on admission was 2.4 g/l. Despite\ncorrection of her body temperature she remains intermittently\nconfused, indifferent and inattentive 24 hours later.</p>\n\n<p>She has no previous medical history of note. Her pulse is 72\nbeats per minute, blood pressure 105/60 mmHg and temperature\n37.0\u00baC.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is unkempt and very thin with poor dentition.\nHer eye movements are abnormal with horizontal nystagmus on lateral\ngaze in both directions and she has a slow, wide-based gait. She\nhas been incontinent of urine on several occasions during the\nadmission.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398386\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199846\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398386\"><span>Alcohol withdrawal</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398388\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199846\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398388\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Normal pressure hydrocephalus</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398390\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199846\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398390\"><span>Wernicke's encephalopathy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398387\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199846\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398387\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Korsakoff's psychosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398389\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199846\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398389\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Subdural haematoma</span></div></div>",
        "id": 297
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Paracetamol poisoning</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The history of headache and the age of the patient are important\nhere.</p>\n\n<p>The alanine aminotransferase is very high - far in excess of\nthat seen in alcoholic hepatitis or gallstone/pancreatic\ndisease.</p>\n\n<p>The history would fit a little with HAV but is not typical.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The combination of coagulopathy renal impairment and marked\nhepatitis strongly suggests accidental or deliberate paracetamol\ntoxicity. This lady was drinking heavily (enzyme inducer) and\ntaking daily maximum paracetamol for her headaches and\nhangover.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>An 18-year-old female was admitted under the surgical team with\nright upper quadrant discomfort, mild jaundice, and nausea. She had\na history of headaches which were not sinister in character. She\nadmitted to drinking heavily on four nights of the week. The\nsurgical registrar requested a review.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she was generally well but jaundiced. There were\nno signs of chronic liver disease and there was no organomegaly.\nShe had a mildly tender right upper quadrant. She stated that she\nwas feeling much better than she had the previous day.</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>132 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cells</th>\n<td>9.0 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(1.5-7)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>150 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>92 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>46 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>128 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>9000 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>120 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Gamma gluteryltransferase</th>\n<td>100 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Smooth muscle antibody</th>\n<td>Not detected</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti mitochondrial antibody</th>\n<td>Not detected</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Prothrombin time</th>\n<td>20 seconds</td>\n<td>(Control 10 seconds)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>143 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>4.0 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>14.0 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum creatinine</th>\n<td>200 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is cause of this patient's problems?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118068\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118068\"><span>Alcoholic hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118069\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118069\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cholelithiasis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118072\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118072\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Pancreatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118071\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118071\"><span>Paracetamol poisoning</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118070\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118070\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis A</span></div></div>",
        "id": 298
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Ultrasound with Doppler</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This child is likely to have portal vein thrombosis resulting\nfrom neonatal cannulation of his umbilical vein following his\npremature delivery.</p>\n\n<p>Portal vein thrombosis should be easily demonstrated on the\nultrasound which is a cheap and a non-invasive procedure.</p>\n\n<p>This should be performed prior to considering hepatic venous\npressure studies.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 14-year-old boy of white Irish parents is admitted with\nhaematemesis. Gastroscopy demonstrates bleeding oesophageal\nvarices.</p>\n\n<p>Despite being born prematurely at 32 weeks, he has been\ncompletely well until presentation.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there are no peripheral stigmata of chronic liver\ndisease but there is a palpable spleen 4 cm below the costal\nmargin.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations showed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatic wedge pressure</th>\n<td>6 mmHg</td>\n<td>(&lt;7)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Inferior vena cava pressure</th>\n<td>3 mmHg</td>\n<td>(&lt;5)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the best initial investigation to\nperform?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117981\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80742\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117981\"><span>Spleno-portogram</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117982\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80742\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117982\"><span>Ultrasound with Doppler</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117979\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80742\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117979\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117978\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80742\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117978\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Laparoscopy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117980\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80742\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117980\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">MRI scan liver</span></div></div>",
        "id": 299
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The high white cell count in the ascites makes spontaneous\nbacterial peritonitis (SBP) much more likely than Budd- Chiari\nsyndrome (BCS), PVT, HCC, or a ruptured pancreatic pseudocyst.</p>\n\n<p>Abdominal pain is often only mild, or even absent in SBP, with\npatients often presenting with otherwise unexplained hepatic\ndecompensation.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 60-year-old woman with known alcoholic liver cirrhosis\npresents with vague abdominal pains, malaise, and nausea.</p>\n\n<p>She has been abstinent since she was diagnosed eight months\nago.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she had moderate ascites and mild, generalised\nabdominal tenderness.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>112 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>WCC</th>\n<td>15 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Prothrombin time</th>\n<td>21 secs</td>\n<td>(11.5-15.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum albumin</th>\n<td>28 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum total bilirubin</th>\n<td>56 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Ascitic fluid albumin</th>\n<td>14 g/L</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Ascitic fluid amylase</th>\n<td>Normal</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Ascitic fluid white cell count</th>\n<td>500 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely reason for her current problem?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117448\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80636\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117448\"><span>Hepatic vein thrombosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117452\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80636\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117452\"><span>Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117450\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80636\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117450\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Portal vein thrombosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117451\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80636\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117451\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Primary liver cancer</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117449\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80636\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117449\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Pancreatic pseudocyst rupture</span></div></div>",
        "id": 300
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>>80%</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Liver transplantation is very effective in primary biliary\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> - the five year survival is more than 80%.</p>\n\n<p>An estimated 10% to 40% of patients develop clinical,\nbiochemical, and histologic changes consistent with recurrent PBC\nafter liver transplantation. However, the presence of recurrent PBC\ndoes not appear to affect either graft or patient survival\nrates.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 50-year-old woman presents with a three month history of\npruritus and lethargy. She is known to have hypothyroidism. She\ndenies regular alcohol intake.</p>\n\n<p>On examination there is evidence of excoriations and\nxanthelasma.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood results are as follows:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>75 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>84 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>465 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>GGT</th>\n<td>390 IU/L</td>\n<td>(4-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bil</th>\n<td>15 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.2</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound scan is normal with normal liver parenchyma\nand no biliary duct dilatation.</p>\n\n<p>What is the five year survival if this woman were to have a\nliver transplant for her underlying condition?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398014\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199771\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398014\"><span>&gt;60%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398012\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199771\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398012\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">&gt;40%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398013\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199771\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398013\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">&gt;50%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398015\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199771\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398015\"><span>&gt;80%</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398011\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199771\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398011\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">&gt;20%</span></div></div>",
        "id": 301
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Octreotide</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders, Small instestinal disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Somatostatin analogues are the treatment of choice for carcinoid symptoms.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/296\">carcinoid syndrome</a> as revealed by the grossly\nelevated urine 5 HIAA concentrations.</p>\n\n<p>Carcinoid is a slow growing neuroendocrine tumour and symptoms\nof diarrhoea and flushes occur as a consequence of metastases to\nthe liver and hence systemic release of vasoactive compounds such\nas 5-HT and bradykinin.</p>\n\n<p>The best treatment for symptoms of carcinoid is the somatostatin\nanalogue, octreotide, which improves symptoms and prognosis in\ncarcinoid syndrome.</p>\n\n<p>Other potential treatments following resistance or failure of\noctreotide include hepatic artery embolisation.</p>\n\n<p>In this case the treatment for the diarrhoea will be through\ntreating the underlying diagnosis, which is carcinoid.\nCyproheptadine is not a first line treatment for diarrhoea and in\nfact may cause diarrnoea as a side effect.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 52-year-old female presents with a six month history of weight\nloss and diarrhoea.</p>\n\n<p>Over this period she had lost approximately 10 kg in weight and\nwas aware of watery diarrhoea three to four times daily. She was\nalso aware of occasional flushes which she had experienced since\nthe menopause at the age of 49 but had become more frequent of\nlate. She had previously been well with no other medical history.\nShe took no medication. She was a non-smoker and drank\napproximately 12 units of alcohol weekly.</p>\n\n<p>On examination, she had a reddish complexion and had a BMI of 24\nkg/m<sup>2</sup>. She had a pulse of 88 beats per minute regular\nand a blood pressure of 122/88 mmHg. There were no abnormalities on\ncardiovascular or respiratory examination but abdominal examination\nrevealed two finger breadth hepatomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations revealed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>145 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White blood cells</th>\n<td>8.5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>301 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"3\" style=\"border: currentColor; border-image: none;\">\n&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>144 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>4.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>3.9 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum creatinine</th>\n<td>110 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"3\" style=\"border: currentColor; border-image: none;\">\n&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>125 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum alanine aminotransferase</th>\n<td>40 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>12 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"3\" style=\"border: currentColor; border-image: none;\">\n&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>24hr Urine 5-Hydroxyindoleacetic acid (5-HIAA)</th>\n<td>100 mg/d</td>\n<td>(&lt;5)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Abdominal ultrasound scan showed numerous echo-dense deposits\nwithin the liver.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most appropriate treatment for\nthis patient's diarrhoea?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117822\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80710\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117822\"><span>Octreotide</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117818\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80710\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117818\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cyproheptadine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117820\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80710\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117820\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Loperamide</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117819\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80710\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117819\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ketanserin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117821\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80710\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117821\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Methysergide</span></div></div>",
        "id": 302
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Terlipressin</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The diagnosis here is <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/402\">hepatorenal syndrome</a> and more\nspecifically, <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/402\">hepatorenal syndrome</a> type 2.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/402\">Hepatorenal syndrome</a> type 2 is characterised by a moderate and\nstable reduction in renal function, hypotension and diuretic\nresistance.</p>\n\n<p>In the treatment of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/402\">hepatorenal syndrome</a> attention has turned to\nagonists of vasopressin V1 receptors such as terlipressin. This\ncauses splanchnic vascoconstriction which may reverse the early\nsplanchnic vasodilatation seen in hepatorenal syndrome. Small\nstudies have demonstrated the utility of terlipressin in patients\nwith hepatorenal syndrome.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Small studies with dopamine have shown no renal benefit in such\npatients. No evidence exists for the use of dobutamine or\noctreotide in these circumstances.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 45-year-old man was admitted with worsening ascites. He was\ndiagnosed with decompensated alcoholic liver disease.</p>\n\n<p>He was subsequently treated with spironolcatone 100 mg od and\nfurosemide 40 mg od and he was administered an intravenous albumin\ninfusion.</p>\n\n<p>Over the next 10 days in hospital he developed oliguria and his\nserum creatinine rose from 130 \u00b5mol/L to 380 \u00b5mol/L (60-110). The\ndiuretics were stopped but his serum creatinine did not improve.\nUrine dipstick examination revealed no proteinuria or\nhaematuria.</p>\n\n<p>Ultrasound of the kidneys was normal. Examination of the ascitic\nfluid did not reveal any evidence of microbial infection. His blood\npressure was maintained at 118/70 mm/Hg.</p>\n\n<p>Which drug, given intravenously, is most likely to improve his\nrenal function?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117904\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80727\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117904\"><span>Dopamine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117907\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80727\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117907\"><span>Terlipressin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117906\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80727\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117906\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Prostacycline</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117903\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80727\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117903\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Dobutamine</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117905\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80727\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117905\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Octreotide</span></div></div>",
        "id": 303
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>AST more than twice the level of ALT</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Aspartate aminotransferase (AST) more than twice the level of\nalanine aminotransferase (ALT) is characteristic of alcoholic liver\ndisease.</p>\n\n<p>Often the ALT is normal or only very mildly elevated, an ALT\n&gt;1000 should raise the possibility of an alternative diagnosis\nsuch as ischaemia or drug toxicity.</p>\n\n<p>An isolated raised alkaline phosphatase should raised the\npossibility of biliary disease first and foremost. Though it may be\nelevated in <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1116\">alcoholic liver disease</a> it is not characterisitic of\nthe condition.&nbsp; A low albumin may be found in liver disease,\nmalnutrition or chronic illness of any cause and ALT &gt; AST is\nnot a specific feature of alcoholic liver disease.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 44-year-old man is noted to have abnormal liver function\ntests. He denies regular alcohol intake.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is confused, there is no asterixis. Abdominal\nexamination reveals 3 cm hepatomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following blood results is characteristic of\nalcoholic liver disease?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398120\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199792\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398120\"><span>Low albumin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398118\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199792\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398118\"><span>AST more than twice the level of ALT</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398119\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199792\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398119\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Isolated elevated ALP</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398117\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199792\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398117\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">ALT &gt; AST</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398116\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199792\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398116\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">ALT &gt; 1000</span></div></div>",
        "id": 304
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Mixed essential cryoglobulinaemia</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This gentleman has renal failure with evidence of a primary\nrenal pathology: significant proteinuria, relative\nhypertension.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/128\">Hepatitis C</a> infection is strongly associated with mixed\nessential <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/870\">cryoglobulinaemia</a> which may produce mesangiocapillary\n(also known as membranoproliferative) glomerulonephritis. This\ncondition is associated with renal impairment, systemic vasculitic\nmanifestations (including neuropathy, skin manifestations), and\narterial thrombosis.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/402\">Hepatorenal syndrome</a> is a diagnosis of exclusion and\nrequires:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>correction of hypovolaemia</li>\n\n<li>withdrawal of any diuretics</li>\n\n<li>treatment of sepsis, and</li>\n\n<li>exclusion of a primary renal pathology prior to diagnosis.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>In <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/402\">hepatorenal syndrome</a>, the kidneys are functionally normal and\nbiopsy is normal; where patients in this situation receive liver\ntransplantation the kidneys will almost always resume normal\nfunction. The urinary sodium and urine dipstick results given here\nindicate a primary renal pathology.</p>\n\n<p>The ascitic tap results indicate that ascites is due to portal\nhypertension (serum albumin ascites gradient &gt;11 g/L) and do not\nsupport the presence of infection within the ascitic fluid,\ncounting against both abdominal tuberculosis, and spontaneous\nbacterial peritonitis.</p>\n\n<p>In the absence of symptoms, a urine dipstick indicating a trace\nof leukocytes and negative nitrites is poorly predictive of the\npresence of a urinary tract infection; additionally this diagnosis\ndoes not adequately explain the degree of proteinuria or renal\nimpairment.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 33-year-old man with chronic hepatitis C is admitted with\ngeneral deterioration, he has no specific symptoms.</p>\n\n<p>He has missed many of his previous outpatient appointments and\ncurrently is not receiving any treatment.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is generally unwell with a temperature of\n37.4\u00b0C, blood pressure of 130/72 mmHg, and appears jaundiced with\nthe presence of ascites.</p>\n\n<p>His investigations reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>133 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>4.3 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>21 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum Creatinine</th>\n<td>336 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>78 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>92 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alk phosphatase</th>\n<td>267 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>30 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urine sodium</th>\n<td>60 mmol/L</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"3\" style=\"border:none; background:none;\">&nbsp;</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th rowspan=\"4\">Urine dipstick</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">+ Blood</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\">+++ Protein</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Leukocytes trace</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Nitrites negative</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Ascitic fluid analysis:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>RBC</th>\n<td>1,231/mm<sup>3</sup></td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>WBC</th>\n<td>190/mm<sup>3</sup> (60% lymphocytes)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>12 g/L</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117722\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80690\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117722\"><span>Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117720\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80690\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117720\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatorenal syndrome</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117721\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80690\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117721\"><span>Mixed essential cryoglobulinaemia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117719\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80690\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117719\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Urinary tract infection</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117718\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80690\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117718\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Abdominal tuberculosis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 305
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Perinatal transmission</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Perinatal transmission is the most common route of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a>\ninfection - the infection rate is 90% in infants born to HBeAg\n(<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> envelope antigen) positive mothers.</p>\n\n<p>Blood inoculation through unclean needles is not the commonest\nroute of transmission of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> but this remains\nimportant.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/126\">Hepatitis A</a> is transmitted through the faeco-oral route and\ningestion of uncooked shellfish.</p>\n\n<p>Sexual transmission comprises 30% of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> infections in\ndeveloped countries.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press;\n2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>You review a 18-year-old man in the gastroenterology clinic. The\nlast correspondence states he is known to have hepatitis B. He\nrecently moved to the United Kingdom from India.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most common route of hepatitis B\ntransmission worldwide?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398088\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199786\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398088\"><span>Perinatal transmission</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398089\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199786\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398089\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Sexual transmission</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398087\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199786\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398087\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Faeco-oral route</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398086\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199786\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398086\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Blood inoculation through needles</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398090\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199786\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398090\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Uncooked shellfish</span></div></div>",
        "id": 306
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Haemochromatosis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Clinical signs of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> include hepatomegaly,\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> and splenomegaly. Patients may have cardiomyopathy and\nendocrine complications including diabetes mellitus, hypogonadism,\npanhypopituitarism and testicular atrophy. The term 'bronze\ndiabetes' comes from the skin pigmentation which is seen in\nthese patients. Chondrocalcinosis and arthritis may also develop.\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/369\">Hepatocellular carcinoma</a> should be excluded especially in those\nwith <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> with three to six monthly alpha fetoprotein and\nultrasound.</p>\n\n<p>Many patients with non-alcoholic fatty liver disease are\nasymptomatic. The diagnosis is usually made by incidentally raised\naminotransferases or ultrasound scan demonstrating a fatty liver.\nRight upper quadrant pain may be reported and patients often have\nhepatomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> is a cholestatic disorder which\naffects middle-aged women in 90% of cases. There is an association\nwith autoimmune diseases. Patients have stigmata of chronic liver\ndisease; other clinical signs include xanthelasma and excoriations\nas a result of pruritus.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">Primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> is associated with inflammatory\nbowel disease. Patients often present with pruritus, intermittent\njaundice and right upper quadrant pain. Features of cholangitis\n(fever, pain and jaundice) usually occur subsequent to\ninstrumentation such as endoscopic retrograde\ncholangiopancreatography (ERCP). Examination reveals signs of\nchronic liver disease and signs of portal hypertension may be\npresent.</p>\n\n<p>Wilson's disease presents between the ages of three and 40\nyears. Acute hepatitis, <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1010\">acute liver failure</a> and decompensated\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> are all recognised with Wilson's disease.\nNeuropsychiatric features are common in adolescence and early\nadulthood with behavioural change, parkinsonism and cognitive\nimpairment. Kayser-Fleischer rings are seen in patients with\nneurological disease.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G, <cite>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology\nand Hepatology.</cite> Oxford: Oxford University Press; 2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>You review a 45-year-old man in the gastroenterology clinic who\nhas been referred by his GP with abnormal liver function tests. The\nonly past medical history is a recent diagnosis of diabetes\nmellitus.</p>\n\n<p>On direct questioning he denies alcohol intake or intravenous\ndrug use. There is no travel history.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is tanned, there is evidence of clubbing and\nhe has spider naevi over the anterior chest wall. Abdominal\nexamination reveals tender hepatomegaly 4 cm below the costal\nmargin.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397960\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397960\"><span>Wilson's disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397956\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397956\"><span>Haemochromatosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397957\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397957\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397958\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397958\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397959\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199760\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397959\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 307
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Start IV piperacillin-tazobactam</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient is suffering from decompensation of previously\nstable liver failure. He is encephalopathic. The likely cause is\nsepsis and in the presence of abdominal pain and a lack of other\nfeatures to localise a source of sepsis a diagnosis of SBP should\nbe considered highly likely.</p>\n\n<p>A diagnostic tap will diagnose SBP if present or exclude it if\nnot - this is a very common cause of deterioration in such\npatients. It is important to start antibiotics promptly pending the\nresults of an ascitic analysis. Whilst therapeutic paracentesis\nwill be necessary in light of the large volume tense ascites it\nwould be advisable to consider doing this with FFP cover.</p>\n\n<p>Increasing the dose of diruretics will not act sufficiently\nquickly to obviate the need for paracentesis and the serum sodium\nis already low, increased doses of diuretics are likely to push\nthis lower.</p>\n\n<p>Thrombocytopenia is predominantly a result of functional\nhypersplenism due to portal hypertension. Platelets need only be\nadministered if there is marked thrombocytopenia and bleeding or a\nneed to perform an investigation or intervention with a significant\nrisk of bleeding.</p>\n\n<p>Oral neomycin has been used in the management of chronic hepatic\nencephalopathy in order to reduce gastrointestinal bacterial load\n(and ammonia production). Its long-term use is associated with the\nusual complications of aminogluycoside therapy due to a degree of\nsystemic absorption.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old male, known to have advanced cryptogenic liver\ncirrhosis, presents with acute onset confusion and abdominal\npain.</p>\n\n<p>His wife claims that over the last few days his abdomen has\nbecome increasingly distended, however she is more concerned about\nhis being disoriented to time and place. The patient was previously\ncontrolled on 100 mg of spironolactone daily together with 2 mg of\nbumetanide daily and 10 ml of lactulose bd.</p>\n\n<p>On examination the patient is dyspnoeic and deeply jaundiced\nwith widespread spider naevi. There is some dullness at the lung\nbases but the chest is otherwise clear. There is tense ascites with\neversion of the umbilicus together with distended abdominal veins.\nAsterixis is also noted. He is confused to time and place and is\nafebrile. A urine dipstick is negative.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>103 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>48 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>102 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>14 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>2.8</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>128 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>3.0 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>4.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum creatinine</th>\n<td>90 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum albumin</th>\n<td>28 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum bilirubin</th>\n<td>95 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum GGT</th>\n<td>59 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum ALT</th>\n<td>60 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following will constitute the best initial\nmanagement?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118145\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80775\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118145\"><span>Increase dose of spironolactone</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118143\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80775\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118143\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Give 4 units of platelets</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118147\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80775\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118147\"><span>Start IV piperacillin-tazobactam</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118146\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80775\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118146\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Start oral neomycin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118144\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80775\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118144\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Large volume paracentesis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 308
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/847\">Primary sclerosing cholangitis</a> (PSC) is characterised by biliary\nstricturing and dilatation. It is associated with inflammatory\nbowel disease. Patients often present with pruritus, intermittent\njaundice and right upper quadrant pain.</p>\n\n<p>Examination reveals signs of chronic liver disease and signs of\nportal hypertension may be present. Liver function tests show a\ncholestatic picture and bilirubin often fluctuates.</p>\n\n<p>Ursodeoxycholic acid is used for pruritus. Deficiencies of\nvitamins A, D, E and K should be corrected if present. Liver\ntransplantation has 80-90% five year survival.</p>\n\n<p>Clinical signs of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/134\">haemochromatosis</a> include hepatomegaly,\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> and splenomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Patients may have cardiomyopathy and endocrine complications\ninclude:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Diabetes mellitus</li>\n\n<li>Hypogonadism</li>\n\n<li>Panhypopituitarism, and</li>\n\n<li>Testicular atrophy.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The term 'bronze diabetes' comes from the skin\npigmentation which is seen in these patients. Chondrocalcinosis and\narthritis may also develop.</p>\n\n<p>Many patients with non-alcoholic fatty liver disease are\nasymptomatic. The diagnosis is usually made by incidentally raised\naminotransferases or ultrasound scan demonstrating a fatty liver.\nRight upper quadrant pain may be reported and patients often have\nhepatomegaly.</p>\n\n<p>Primary biliary <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> is a cholestatic disorder which\naffects middle-aged women in 90% of cases. There is an association\nwith autoimmune diseases. Patients have stigmata of chronic liver\ndisease; other clinical signs include xanthelasma and excoriations\nas a result of pruritus.</p>\n\n<p>Wilson's disease presents between the ages of three and 40\nyears. Acute hepatitis, <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1010\">acute liver failure</a> and decompensated\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a> are all recognised with Wilson's disease.\nNeuropsychiatric features are common in adolescence and early\nadulthood with behavioural change, parkinsonism and cognitive\nimpairment. Kayser-Fleischer rings are seen in patients with\nneurological disease.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Travis SPL, et al. <cite>Pocket Consultant\nGastroenterology.</cite> Oxford: Blackwell Publishing; 2005</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 40-year-old man known to have ulcerative colitis is referred\nto the gastroenterology clinic with abnormal liver function tests.\nHe reports intermittent jaundice and pruritus.</p>\n\n<p>On direct questioning he admits to recent right upper quadrant\npain.</p>\n\n<p>Blood results are included in the referral letter:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Hb</th>\n<td>150 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>82 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>350 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>WBC</th>\n<td>5.5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Neut</th>\n<td>3.5 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(1.5-7)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ESR</th>\n<td>10 mm/hour</td>\n<td>(0-15)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>CRP</th>\n<td>8 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bil</th>\n<td>20 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>70 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>345 U/L</td>\n<td>(45-105)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alb</th>\n<td>36 g/L</td>\n<td>(37-49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>GGT</th>\n<td>200 U/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;50)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>55 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>What is the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398068\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398068\"><span>Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398066\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398066\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Haemochromatosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398070\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398070\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Wilson's disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398067\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398067\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Non-alcoholic fatty liver disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398069\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199782\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398069\"><span>Primary sclerosing cholangitis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 309
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Vaccination</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This pattern of serology suggests vaccination against hepatitis\nB.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>You are reviewing blood results and find the following serology\nresults.</p>\n\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>HBsAg</th>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>HbeAg</th>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti-HBs</th>\n<td>+</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti-HBe</th>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Anti-HBc</th>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which of the following has caused this pattern?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201058\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201058\"><span>Acute liver failure caused by hepatitis B</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201061\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201061\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Recovery from infection with hepatitis B</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201062\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201062\"><span>Vaccination</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201059\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201059\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatitis B carrier status</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"201060\" name=\"rdBtnOption+129825\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"201060\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Incubation of infection with hepatitis B</span></div></div>",
        "id": 310
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>pH 7.25</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>A pH of less than 7.3 is a poor prognostic factor for this\npatient.</p>\n\n<p>The criteria for transfer to a specialist unit are:</p>\n\n<ul class=\"style1\">\n<li>Encephalopathy</li>\n\n<li>INR: &gt;2.0 at &lt;48 hours, or &gt;3.5 at &lt;72 hours</li>\n\n<li>Serum creatinine: &gt;200 \u03bcmol/L</li>\n\n<li>Blood pH: &lt;7.3</li>\n\n<li>Systolic BP: &lt;80 mmHg.</li>\n</ul></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 24-year-old woman has ingested an unknown quantity of\nparacetamol tablets four hours ago.</p>\n\n<p>She now presents with nausea, vomiting, anorexia and right\nsubchondral pain.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following features suggest that she should be\ntransferred to the liver unit?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117996\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80745\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117996\"><span>Heart rate 120 BPM</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117994\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80745\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117994\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">ALT 800 units/L</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117995\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80745\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117995\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Blood glucose 5 mmol/L</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117997\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80745\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117997\"><span>pH 7.25</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117993\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80745\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117993\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Systolic BP 100 mmHg</span></div></div>",
        "id": 311
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Hydatid serology</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>Liver disorders</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Hydatid infection was previously endemic in sheep farming regions. Asymptomatic, calcified cystic lesions in the liver are typical of hydatid cysts.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Asymptomatic, calcified cystic lesions in the liver are typical\nof hydatid cysts.</p>\n\n<p>Hydatid infection was endemic in sheep farming regions (such as\nWales or New Zealand) in the past and sheep dogs were infected by\neating infected offal. Humans contract hydatids via faecal/oral\nspread from dogs.</p>\n\n<p>The liver cysts are usually asymptomatic and calcification\nusually denotes a non-viable cyst.</p>\n\n<p>Ultrasonography is probably the most helpful initial test since\nit can usually differentiate a simple cyst from other cystic\nlesions. It should also be used for follow up studies.</p>\n\n<p>Hydatid serology has a sensitivity of 80-90%. If hydatid\nserology is negative then further imaging (CT/MRI) +/- aspiration\nmay be required to make a diagnosis.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/268\">Melanoma</a> metastases are not typically cystic and calcified.</p>\n\n<p>Basal cell carcinomas are very common in those who work outside\nin the southern hemisphere; liver metastases are very uncommon.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 75-year-old retired farmer from mid-Wales was found to have\nvery mildly deranged liver function tests during a routine health\ncheck up.</p>\n\n<p>He had an ultrasound scan which demonstrated multiple cystic\nlesions in the right lobe of the liver ranging in size from 1-8 cm\nin diameter. The larger cysts have a calcified appearance.</p>\n\n<p>He had a melanoma removed from his back 20 years ago and has had\nmultiple basal cell carcinomas removed from his head, face, and\narms in recent years.</p>\n\n<p>Which investigation should be carried out next?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117669\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80680\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117669\"><span>ERCP</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117670\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80680\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117670\"><span>Hydatid serology</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117672\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80680\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117672\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Liver biopsy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117671\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80680\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117671\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Needle aspiration</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117668\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80680\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117668\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">CT scan</span></div></div>",
        "id": 312
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This is a case of non-alcoholic steatohepatitis, the diagnosis\nof which is made only by histology of liver biopsy which shows\nlesions suggestive of ethanol intake in a patient known to consume\nless than 40 g of alcohol per week.</p>\n\n<p>The diagnosis is supported by the presence of obesity,\nhyperglycaemia, and hyperechogenic hepatic parenchyma.</p>\n\n<p>In alcoholic hepatitis the AST is normally raised more than the\nALT typically with a ratio of at least 2:1.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 35-year-old obese Afro-Caribbean lady presents with abnormal\nliver function tests. She claims to be a teetotaler and her BMI is\n30 kg/m<sup>2</sup>.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations reveal the following results.</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>140 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>U+Es</th>\n<td>Normal</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>25 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1-22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Aspartate transaminase</th>\n<td>140 U/L</td>\n<td>(1-31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alanine transaminase</th>\n<td>155 U/L</td>\n<td>(5-35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Alkaline phosphatase</th>\n<td>160 U/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Random blood glucose</th>\n<td>11.2 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.0-6.0)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis A IgG</th>\n<td>Positive</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Hepatitis B and C screening</th>\n<td>Negative</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Antinuclear antibodies</th>\n<td>1:16 titre</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Ultrasound abdomen reveals hyperechogenic hepatic\nparenchyma.</p>\n\n<p>Liver biopsy reveals lesions suggestive of alcoholic liver\ndisease.</p>\n\n<p>On review of her notes, liver function tests performed six\nmonths previously showed similar values.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118142\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80774\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118142\"><span>Viral hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118141\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80774\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118141\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Primary biliary cirrhosis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118139\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80774\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118139\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Autoimmune hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118140\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80774\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118140\"><span>Non-alcoholic steatohepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118138\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80774\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118138\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Alcoholic liver disease</span></div></div>",
        "id": 313
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Tuberculosis</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has stigmata of chronic liver disease both on\nexamination and on blood tests. The ascitic fluid has a high\n(&gt;11 g/l) serum ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) making it a\ntransudate and consistent with portal hypertension secondary to\nchronic liver disease.</p>\n\n<p>However the fluid has a markedly elevated white cell count which\nis predominantly lymphocytic. This is very suggestive of tubercular\ninfection of ascitic fluid - the clinical findings and high SAAG\nindicate the presence of underlying liver disease which in this\npatient is likely to be due to chronic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/127\">hepatitis B</a> infection. Her\nbackground is one at risk of tuberculosis and the extensive\nlymphadenopathy is also suggestive.</p>\n\n<p>Patients with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/793\">spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</a> will also have a\nhigh (&gt;11 g/L) serum ascites albumin gradient (SAAG) ascitic\nfluid however the white cells will be predominantly neutrophils\n(&gt;500 WBCs/mm<sup>3</sup> and &gt;50% neutrophils).</p>\n\n<p>Lymphoma may give rise to ascites. This ascites may be rich in\nlymphocytes as in this case but shares more features of malignant\nascites - low SAAG (&lt;11 g/L,&nbsp;indicating an exudate) and often\nvery bloody. Lymphoma may also give rise to chylous ascites (milky\nin colour and rich in fats).</p>\n\n<p>Chronic viral hepatitis would give rise to simple transudative\nascites (high SAAG), normally with very few white cells (certainly\n&lt;500/mm<sup>3</sup>).</p>\n\n<p>The ascites of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/369\">hepatocellular carcinoma</a> can be variable,\ndepending particularly on the presence or absence of underlying\nliver disease. Usually, particularly where there is also <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/278\">cirrhosis</a>\nof the liver, the ascites associated with <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/369\">hepatocellular carcinoma</a>\nshares the same features as that in spontaneous bacterial\nperitonitis (high SAAG, high neutrophil count) but is culture\nnegative and cytology positive.</p>\n\n<p>The ascites alpha-fetoprotein level may be raised but only if\nthe serum value is also raised.</p>\n\n<p>The Ziehl-Neelson has a low sensitivity but is highly predictive\nof active TB if positive.&nbsp;</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 42-year-old woman of Bangladeshi origin presents to the\nEmergency department with abdominal pain and distension. She denies\nany alcohol whatsoever.</p>\n\n<p>Her family report that she has become progressively weaker and\nfrail over the last seven months.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is jaundiced with numerous spider naevi and\nhas mild asterixis. Firm, enlarged lymph nodes can be palpated in\nboth cervical chains and the left axilla. Her abdomen is grossly\ndistended and shifting dullness is present, no organomegaly can be\npalpated. There is pitting oedema to the knee.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood tests reveal:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>73 g/L</td>\n<td>(130 - 180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>14.7 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4 - 11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>102 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150 - 400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Bilirubin</th>\n<td>156 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(1 - 22)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALP</th>\n<td>113 IU/L</td>\n<td>(45 - 10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>ALT</th>\n<td>34 IU/L</td>\n<td>(5 - 35)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>AST</th>\n<td>20 IU/L</td>\n<td>(1 - 31)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Albumin</th>\n<td>19 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(37 - 49)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>C reactive protein</th>\n<td>113 mg/L</td>\n<td>(&lt;10)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.5</td>\n<td>(&lt; 1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>An ascitic tap is performed and 50 mls of clear yellow fluid are\neasily aspirated from the abdominal cavity. Analysis of the fluid\ndemonstrates that the fluid white cell count is 1,670\ncells/mm<sup>3</sup> (22% neutrophils, 75% lymphocytic), red cell\ncount 1,684/mm<sup>3</sup> and albumin is 6 g/L, and both the Gram\nstain and Ziehl-Neelsen stain are negative.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most appropriate diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398221\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199813\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398221\"><span>Chronic viral hepatitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398223\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199813\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398223\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Lymphoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398222\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199813\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398222\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Hepatocellular carcinoma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398224\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199813\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398224\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398225\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199813\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398225\"><span>Tuberculosis</span></div></div>",
        "id": 314
    }
]